# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: image-super-resolution
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:image-super-resolution/convolutional-neural-network-p01] A **convolutional neural network** (**CNN**) is a type of feedforward neural network that learns features via filter (or kernel) optimization.
[src:image-super-resolution/convolutional-neural-network-p01] This type of deep learning network has been applied to process and make predictions from many different types of data including text, images and audio.
[src:image-super-resolution/convolutional-neural-network-p01] CNNs are the de-facto standard in deep learning-based approaches to computer vision and image processing, and have only recently been replaced—in some cases—by newer architectures such as the transformer.
[src:image-super-resolution/convolutional-neural-network-p01] Vanishing gradients and exploding gradients, seen during backpropagation in earlier neural networks, are prevented by the regularization that comes from using shared weights over fewer connections.
[src:image-super-resolution/convolutional-neural-network-p01] For example, for *each* neuron in the fully-connected layer, 10,000 weights would be required for processing an image sized 100 × 100 pixels.
[src:image-super-resolution/convolutional-neural-network-p01] However, applying cascaded *convolution* (or cross-correlation) kernels, only 25 weights for each convolutional layer are required to process 5x5-sized tiles.
[src:image-super-resolution/convolutional-neural-network-p01] Higher-layer features are extracted from wider context windows, compared to lower-layer features.
[src:image-super-resolution/convolutional-neural-network-p01] CNNs are also known as **shift invariant** or **space invariant artificial neural networks**, based on the shared-weight architecture of the convolution kernels or filters that slide along input features and provide translation-equivariant responses known as feature maps.
[src:image-super-resolution/convolutional-neural-network-p01] Counter-intuitively, most convolutional neural networks are not invariant to translation, due to the downsampling operation they apply to the input.
[src:image-super-resolution/convolutional-neural-network-p01] Feedforward neural networks are usually fully connected networks, that is, each neuron in one layer is connected to all neurons in the next layer.
[src:image-super-resolution/convolutional-neural-network-p01] The "full connectivity" of these networks makes them prone to overfitting data.
[src:image-super-resolution/convolutional-neural-network-p01] Convolutional networks were inspired by biological processes in that the connectivity pattern between neurons resembles the organization of the animal visual cortex.
[src:image-super-resolution/convolutional-neural-network-p01] Individual cortical neurons respond to stimuli only in a restricted region of the visual field known as the receptive field.
[src:image-super-resolution/convolutional-neural-network-p01] The receptive fields of different neurons partially overlap such that they cover the entire visual field.
[src:image-super-resolution/convolutional-neural-network-p01] CNNs use relatively little pre-processing compared to other image classification algorithms.
[src:image-super-resolution/convolutional-neural-network-p01] This means that the network learns to optimize the filters (or kernels) through automated learning, whereas in traditional algorithms these filters are hand-engineered.
[src:image-super-resolution/convolutional-neural-network-p01] This simplifies and automates the process, enhancing efficiency and scalability overcoming human-intervention bottlenecks.
[src:image-super-resolution/convolutional-neural-network-p01] A convolutional neural network consists of an input layer, hidden layers and an output layer.
[src:image-super-resolution/convolutional-neural-network-p01] In a convolutional neural network, the hidden layers include one or more layers that perform convolutions.
[src:image-super-resolution/convolutional-neural-network-p01] Typically this includes a layer that performs a dot product of the convolution kernel with the layer's input matrix.
[src:image-super-resolution/convolutional-neural-network-p01] This product is usually the Frobenius inner product, and its activation function is commonly ReLU.
[src:image-super-resolution/convolutional-neural-network-p01] As the convolution kernel slides along the input matrix for the layer, the convolution operation generates a feature map, which in turn contributes to the input of the next layer.
[src:image-super-resolution/convolutional-neural-network-p01] This is followed by other layers such as pooling layers, fully connected layers, and normalization layers.
[src:image-super-resolution/convolutional-neural-network-p01] Here it should be noted how close a convolutional neural network is to a matched filter.
[src:image-super-resolution/convolutional-neural-network-p01] (number of inputs) × (feature map height) × (feature map width) × (feature map channels).
[src:image-super-resolution/convolutional-neural-network-p01] Convolutional layers convolve the input and pass its result to the next layer.
[src:image-super-resolution/convolutional-neural-network-p01] This is similar to the response of a neuron in the visual cortex to a specific stimulus.
[src:image-super-resolution/convolutional-neural-network-p01] Each convolutional neuron processes data only for its receptive field.
[src:image-super-resolution/convolutional-neural-network-p01] Although fully connected feedforward neural networks can be used to learn features and classify data, this architecture is generally impractical for larger inputs (e.g., high-resolution images), which would require massive numbers of neurons because each pixel is a relevant input feature.
[src:image-super-resolution/convolutional-neural-network-p01] A fully connected layer for an image of size 100 × 100 has 10,000 weights for *each* neuron in the second layer.
[src:image-super-resolution/convolutional-neural-network-p01] Convolution reduces the number of free parameters, allowing the network to be deeper.
[src:image-super-resolution/convolutional-neural-network-p01] For example, using a 5 × 5 tiling region, each with the same shared weights, requires only 25 neurons.
[src:image-super-resolution/convolutional-neural-network-p01] Using shared weights means there are many fewer parameters, which helps avoid the vanishing gradients and exploding gradients problems seen during backpropagation in earlier neural networks.
[src:image-super-resolution/convolutional-neural-network-p01] To speed processing, standard convolutional layers can be replaced by depthwise separable convolutional layers, which are based on a depthwise convolution followed by a pointwise convolution.
[src:image-super-resolution/convolutional-neural-network-p01] The *depthwise convolution* is a spatial convolution applied independently over each channel of the input tensor, while the *pointwise convolution* is a standard convolution restricted to the use of $1\times 1$ kernels.
[src:image-super-resolution/convolutional-neural-network-p01] Convolutional networks may include local and/or global pooling layers along with traditional convolutional layers.
[src:image-super-resolution/convolutional-neural-network-p01] Pooling layers reduce the dimensions of data by combining the outputs of neuron clusters at one layer into a single neuron in the next layer.
[src:image-super-resolution/convolutional-neural-network-p01] Local pooling combines small clusters, tiling sizes such as 2 × 2 are commonly used.
[src:image-super-resolution/convolutional-neural-network-p01] Global pooling acts on all the neurons of the feature map.
[src:image-super-resolution/convolutional-neural-network-p01] There are two common types of pooling in popular use: max and average.
[src:image-super-resolution/convolutional-neural-network-p01] *Max pooling* uses the maximum value of each local cluster of neurons in the feature map, while *average pooling* takes the average value.
[src:image-super-resolution/convolutional-neural-network-p01] Fully connected layers connect every neuron in one layer to every neuron in another layer.
[src:image-super-resolution/convolutional-neural-network-p01] It is the same as a traditional multilayer perceptron neural network (MLP).
[src:image-super-resolution/convolutional-neural-network-p01] Each neuron in the fully connected layer receives input from all the neurons in the previous layer.
[src:image-super-resolution/convolutional-neural-network-p01] These inputs are weighted and summed with the corresponding biases, and then passed through an activation function to perform a nonlinear transformation, generating the output.
[src:image-super-resolution/convolutional-neural-network-p01] The flattened matrix goes through a fully connected layer to classify the images.
[src:image-super-resolution/convolutional-neural-network-p01] In neural networks, each neuron receives input from some number of locations in the previous layer.
[src:image-super-resolution/convolutional-neural-network-p01] In a convolutional layer, each neuron receives input from only a restricted area of the previous layer called the neuron's *receptive field*.
[src:image-super-resolution/convolutional-neural-network-p01] Whereas, in a fully connected layer, the receptive field is the *entire previous layer*.
[src:image-super-resolution/convolutional-neural-network-p01] Thus, in each convolutional layer, each neuron takes input from a larger area in the input than previous layers.
[src:image-super-resolution/convolutional-neural-network-p01] This is due to applying the convolution over and over, which takes the value of a pixel into account, as well as its surrounding pixels.
[src:image-super-resolution/convolutional-neural-network-p01] When using dilated layers, the number of pixels in the receptive field remains constant, but the field is more sparsely populated as its dimensions grow when combining the effect of several layers.
[src:image-super-resolution/convolutional-neural-network-p01] To manipulate the receptive field size as desired, there are some alternatives to the standard convolutional layer.
[src:image-super-resolution/convolutional-neural-network-p01] For example, atrous or dilated convolution expands the receptive field size without increasing the number of parameters by interleaving visible and blind regions.
[src:image-super-resolution/convolutional-neural-network-p01] Moreover, a single dilated convolutional layer can comprise filters with multiple dilation ratios, thus having a variable receptive field size.
[src:image-super-resolution/convolutional-neural-network-p01] Each neuron in a neural network computes an output value by applying a specific function to the input values received from the receptive field in the previous layer.
[src:image-super-resolution/convolutional-neural-network-p01] The function that is applied to the input values is determined by a vector of weights and a bias (typically real numbers).
[src:image-super-resolution/convolutional-neural-network-p01] Learning consists of iteratively adjusting these biases and weights.
[src:image-super-resolution/convolutional-neural-network-p01] The vectors of weights and biases are called *filters* and represent particular features of the input (e.g., a particular shape).
[src:image-super-resolution/convolutional-neural-network-p01] A distinguishing feature of CNNs is that many neurons can share the same filter.
[src:image-super-resolution/convolutional-neural-network-p01] This reduces the memory footprint because a single bias and a single vector of weights are used across all receptive fields that share that filter, as opposed to each receptive field having its own bias and vector weighting.
[src:image-super-resolution/convolutional-neural-network-p01] A deconvolutional neural network is essentially the reverse of a CNN.
[src:image-super-resolution/convolutional-neural-network-p01] It consists of deconvolutional layers and unpooling layers.
[src:image-super-resolution/convolutional-neural-network-p01] A deconvolutional layer is the transpose of a convolutional layer.
[src:image-super-resolution/convolutional-neural-network-p01] Specifically, a convolutional layer can be written as a multiplication with a matrix, and a deconvolutional layer is multiplication with the transpose of that matrix.
[src:image-super-resolution/convolutional-neural-network-p01] The max-unpooling layer is the simplest, as it simply copies each entry multiple times.
[src:image-super-resolution/convolutional-neural-network-p01] For example, a 2-by-2 max-unpooling layer is $[x]\mapsto {\begin{bmatrix}x&x\\x&x\end{bmatrix}}$ .
[src:image-super-resolution/convolutional-neural-network-p01] Deconvolution layers are used in image generators.
[src:image-super-resolution/convolutional-neural-network-p01] By default, it creates periodic checkerboard artifact, which can be fixed by upscale-then-convolve.
[src:image-super-resolution/convolutional-neural-network-p01] CNN are often compared to the way the brain achieves vision processing in living organisms.
[src:image-super-resolution/convolutional-neural-network-p01] Work by Hubel and Wiesel in the 1950s and 1960s showed that cat visual cortices contain neurons that individually respond to small regions of the visual field.
[src:image-super-resolution/convolutional-neural-network-p01] Provided the eyes are not moving, the region of visual space within which visual stimuli affect the firing of a single neuron is known as its receptive field.
[src:image-super-resolution/convolutional-neural-network-p01] Neighboring cells have similar and overlapping receptive fields.
[src:image-super-resolution/convolutional-neural-network-p01] Receptive field size and location varies systematically across the cortex to form a complete map of visual space.
[src:image-super-resolution/convolutional-neural-network-p01] The cortex in each hemisphere represents the contralateral visual field.
[src:image-super-resolution/convolutional-neural-network-p01] Hubel and Wiesel also proposed a cascading model of these two types of cells for use in pattern recognition tasks.
[src:image-super-resolution/convolutional-neural-network-p01] In the same paper, Fukushima also introduced the ReLU (rectified linear unit) activation function.
[src:image-super-resolution/convolutional-neural-network-p01] The "neocognitron" was introduced by Fukushima in 1980.
[src:image-super-resolution/convolutional-neural-network-p01] Several supervised and unsupervised learning algorithms have been proposed over the decades to train the weights of a neocognitron.
[src:image-super-resolution/convolutional-neural-network-p01] Today, however, the CNN architecture is usually trained through backpropagation.
[src:image-super-resolution/convolutional-neural-network-p01] Fukushima's ReLU activation function was not used in his neocognitron since all the weights were nonnegative; lateral inhibition was used instead.
[src:image-super-resolution/convolutional-neural-network-p01] The rectifier has become a very popular activation function for CNNs and deep neural networks in general.
[src:image-super-resolution/convolutional-neural-network-p01] The term "convolution" first appears in neural networks in a paper by Toshiteru Homma, Les Atlas, and Robert Marks II at the first Conference on Neural Information Processing Systems in 1987.
[src:image-super-resolution/convolutional-neural-network-p01] Their paper replaced multiplication with convolution in time, inherently providing shift invariance, motivated by and connecting more directly to the signal-processing concept of a filter, and demonstrated it on a speech recognition task.
[src:image-super-resolution/convolutional-neural-network-p01] They also pointed out that as a data-trainable system, convolution is essentially equivalent to correlation since reversal of the weights does not affect the final learned function ("For convenience, we denote * as correlation instead of convolution.
[src:image-super-resolution/convolutional-neural-network-p01] Note that convolving a(t) with b(t) is equivalent to correlating a(-t) with b(t).").
[src:image-super-resolution/convolutional-neural-network-p01] Modern CNN implementations typically do correlation and call it convolution, for convenience, as they did here.
[src:image-super-resolution/convolutional-neural-network-p01] The time delay neural network (TDNN) was introduced in 1987 by Alex Waibel et al. for phoneme recognition and was an early convolutional network exhibiting shift-invariance.
[src:image-super-resolution/convolutional-neural-network-p01] A TDNN is a 1-D convolutional neural net where the convolution is performed along the time axis of the data.
[src:image-super-resolution/convolutional-neural-network-p01] It is the first CNN utilizing weight sharing in combination with a training by gradient descent, using backpropagation.
[src:image-super-resolution/convolutional-neural-network-p01] Thus, while also using a pyramidal structure as in the neocognitron, it performed a global optimization of the weights instead of a local one.
[src:image-super-resolution/convolutional-neural-network-p01] TDNNs are convolutional networks that share weights along the temporal dimension.
[src:image-super-resolution/convolutional-neural-network-p01] They allow speech signals to be processed time-invariantly.
[src:image-super-resolution/convolutional-neural-network-p01] In 1990 Hampshire and Waibel introduced a variant that performs a two-dimensional convolution.
[src:image-super-resolution/convolutional-neural-network-p01] Since these TDNNs operated on spectrograms, the resulting phoneme recognition system was invariant to both time and frequency shifts, as with images processed by a neocognitron.
[src:image-super-resolution/convolutional-neural-network-p01] TDNNs improved the performance of far-distance speech recognition.
[src:image-super-resolution/convolutional-neural-network-p01] (1989) designed a 2-D CNN system to recognize hand-written ZIP Code numbers.
[src:image-super-resolution/convolutional-neural-network-p01] However, the lack of an efficient training method to determine the kernel coefficients of the involved convolutions meant that all the coefficients had to be laboriously hand-designed.
[src:image-super-resolution/convolutional-neural-network-p01] Following the advances in the training of 1-D CNNs by Waibel et al.
[src:image-super-resolution/convolutional-neural-network-p01] (1989) used back-propagation to learn the convolution kernel coefficients directly from images of hand-written numbers.
[src:image-super-resolution/convolutional-neural-network-p01] Learning was thus fully automatic, performed better than manual coefficient design, and was suited to a broader range of image recognition problems and image types.
[src:image-super-resolution/convolutional-neural-network-p01] (1988) used back-propagation to train the convolution kernels of a CNN for alphabets recognition.
[src:image-super-resolution/convolutional-neural-network-p01] The model was called shift-invariant pattern recognition neural network before the name CNN was coined later in the early 1990s.
[src:image-super-resolution/convolutional-neural-network-p01] Wei Zhang et al. also applied the same CNN without the last fully connected layer for medical image object segmentation (1991) and breast cancer detection in mammograms (1994).
[src:image-super-resolution/convolutional-neural-network-p01] This approach became a foundation of modern computer vision.
[src:image-super-resolution/convolutional-neural-network-p01] In 1990 Yamaguchi et al. introduced the concept of max pooling, a fixed filtering operation that calculates and propagates the maximum value of a given region.
[src:image-super-resolution/convolutional-neural-network-p01] They did so by combining TDNNs with max pooling to realize a speaker-independent isolated word recognition system.
[src:image-super-resolution/convolutional-neural-network-p01] In their system they used several TDNNs per word, one for each syllable.
[src:image-super-resolution/convolutional-neural-network-p01] The results of each TDNN over the input signal were combined using max pooling and the outputs of the pooling layers were then passed on to networks performing the actual word classification.
[src:image-super-resolution/convolutional-neural-network-p01] In a variant of the neocognitron called the *cresceptron*, instead of using Fukushima's spatial averaging with inhibition and saturation, J.
[src:image-super-resolution/convolutional-neural-network-p01] Weng et al. in 1993 used max pooling, where a downsampling unit computes the maximum of the activations of the units in its patch, introducing this method into the vision field.
[src:image-super-resolution/convolutional-neural-network-p01] Max pooling is often used in modern CNNs.
[src:image-super-resolution/convolutional-neural-network-p01] LeNet-5, a pioneering 7-level convolutional network by LeCun et al. in 1995, classifies hand-written numbers on checks digitized in 32×32 pixel images.
[src:image-super-resolution/convolutional-neural-network-p01] The ability to process higher-resolution images requires larger and more layers of convolutional neural networks, so this technique is constrained by the availability of computing resources.
[src:image-super-resolution/convolutional-neural-network-p01] It was superior than other commercial courtesy amount reading systems (as of 1995).
[src:image-super-resolution/convolutional-neural-network-p01] The system was integrated in NCR's check reading systems, and fielded in several American banks since June 1996, reading millions of checks per day.
[src:image-super-resolution/convolutional-neural-network-p01] A shift-invariant neural network was proposed by Wei Zhang et al. for image character recognition in 1988.
[src:image-super-resolution/convolutional-neural-network-p01] It is a modified Neocognitron by keeping only the convolutional interconnections between the image feature layers and the last fully connected layer.
[src:image-super-resolution/convolutional-neural-network-p01] The model was trained with back-propagation.
[src:image-super-resolution/convolutional-neural-network-p01] The training algorithm was further improved in 1991 to improve its generalization ability.
[src:image-super-resolution/convolutional-neural-network-p01] The model architecture was modified by removing the last fully connected layer and applied for medical image segmentation (1991) and automatic detection of breast cancer in mammograms (1994).
[src:image-super-resolution/convolutional-neural-network-p01] A different convolution-based design was proposed in 1988 for application to decomposition of one-dimensional electromyography convolved signals via de-convolution.
[src:image-super-resolution/convolutional-neural-network-p01] This design was modified in 1989 to other de-convolution-based designs.
[src:image-super-resolution/convolutional-neural-network-p01] Although CNNs were invented in the 1980s, their breakthrough in the 2000s required fast implementations on graphics processing units (GPUs).
[src:image-super-resolution/convolutional-neural-network-p01] Jung that standard neural networks can be greatly accelerated on GPUs.
[src:image-super-resolution/convolutional-neural-network-p01] Their implementation was 20 times faster than an equivalent implementation on CPU.
[src:image-super-resolution/convolutional-neural-network-p01] In 2005, another paper also emphasised the value of GPGPU for machine learning.
[src:image-super-resolution/convolutional-neural-network-p01] The first GPU-implementation of a CNN was described in 2006 by K.
[src:image-super-resolution/convolutional-neural-network-p01] Their implementation was 4 times faster than an equivalent implementation on CPU.
[src:image-super-resolution/convolutional-neural-network-p01] In the same period, GPUs were also used for unsupervised training of deep belief networks.
[src:image-super-resolution/convolutional-neural-network-p01] In 2010, Dan Ciresan et al. at IDSIA trained deep feedforward networks on GPUs.
[src:image-super-resolution/convolutional-neural-network-p01] In 2011, they extended this to CNNs, accelerating by 60 compared to training CPU.
[src:image-super-resolution/convolutional-neural-network-p01] In 2011, the network won an image recognition contest where they achieved superhuman performance for the first time.
[src:image-super-resolution/convolutional-neural-network-p01] Then they won more competitions and achieved state of the art on several benchmarks.
[src:image-super-resolution/convolutional-neural-network-p01] Subsequently, AlexNet, a similar GPU-based CNN by Alex Krizhevsky et al. won the ImageNet Large Scale Visual Recognition Challenge 2012.
[src:image-super-resolution/convolutional-neural-network-p01] It was an early catalytic event for the AI boom.
[src:image-super-resolution/convolutional-neural-network-p01] Compared to the training of CNNs using GPUs, not much attention was given to CPU.
[src:image-super-resolution/convolutional-neural-network-p01] (Viebke et al 2019) parallelizes CNN by thread- and SIMD-level parallelism that is available on the Intel Xeon Phi.
[src:image-super-resolution/convolutional-neural-network-p01] In the past, traditional multilayer perceptron (MLP) models were used for image recognition.
[src:image-super-resolution/convolutional-neural-network-p01] However, the full connectivity between nodes caused the curse of dimensionality, and was computationally intractable with higher-resolution images.
[src:image-super-resolution/convolutional-neural-network-p01] A 1000×1000-pixel image with RGB color channels has 3 million weights per fully-connected neuron, which is too high to feasibly process efficiently at scale.
[src:image-super-resolution/convolutional-neural-network-p01] For example, in CIFAR-10, images are only of size 32×32×3 (32 wide, 32 high, 3 color channels), so a single fully connected neuron in the first hidden layer of a regular neural network would have 32*32*3 = 3,072 weights.
[src:image-super-resolution/convolutional-neural-network-p01] Also, such network architecture does not take into account the spatial structure of data, treating input pixels which are far apart in the same way as pixels that are close together.
[src:image-super-resolution/convolutional-neural-network-p01] This ignores locality of reference in data with a grid-topology (such as images), both computationally and semantically.
[src:image-super-resolution/convolutional-neural-network-p01] Thus, full connectivity of neurons is wasteful for purposes such as image recognition that are dominated by spatially local input patterns.
[src:image-super-resolution/convolutional-neural-network-p01] Convolutional neural networks are variants of multilayer perceptrons, designed to emulate the behavior of a visual cortex.
[src:image-super-resolution/convolutional-neural-network-p01] These models mitigate the challenges posed by the MLP architecture by exploiting the strong spatially local correlation present in natural images.
[src:image-super-resolution/convolutional-neural-network-p01] Together, these properties allow CNNs to achieve better generalization on vision problems.
[src:image-super-resolution/convolutional-neural-network-p01] Weight sharing dramatically reduces the number of free parameters learned, thus lowering the memory requirements for running the network and allowing the training of larger, more powerful networks.
[src:image-super-resolution/convolutional-neural-network-p01] A CNN architecture is formed by a stack of distinct layers that transform the input volume into an output volume (e.g. holding the class scores) through a differentiable function.
[src:image-super-resolution/convolutional-neural-network-p01] A few distinct types of layers are commonly used.
[src:image-super-resolution/convolutional-neural-network-p01] The convolutional layer is the core building block of a CNN.
[src:image-super-resolution/convolutional-neural-network-p01] The layer's parameters consist of a set of learnable filters (or kernels), which have a small receptive field, but extend through the full depth of the input volume.
[src:image-super-resolution/convolutional-neural-network-p01] During the forward pass, each filter is convolved across the width and height of the input volume, computing the dot product between the filter entries and the input, producing a 2-dimensional activation map of that filter.
[src:image-super-resolution/convolutional-neural-network-p01] As a result, the network learns filters that activate when it detects some specific type of feature at some spatial position in the input.
[src:image-super-resolution/convolutional-neural-network-p01] Stacking the activation maps for all filters along the depth dimension forms the full output volume of the convolution layer.
[src:image-super-resolution/convolutional-neural-network-p01] Every entry in the output volume can thus also be interpreted as an output of a neuron that looks at a small region in the input.
[src:image-super-resolution/convolutional-neural-network-p01] Each entry in an activation map use the same set of parameters that define the filter.
[src:image-super-resolution/convolutional-neural-network-p01] Self-supervised learning has been adapted for use in convolutional layers by using sparse patches with a high-mask ratio and a global response normalization layer.
[src:image-super-resolution/convolutional-neural-network-p01] When dealing with high-dimensional inputs such as images, it is impractical to connect neurons to all neurons in the previous volume because such a network architecture does not take the spatial structure of the data into account.
[src:image-super-resolution/convolutional-neural-network-p01] Convolutional networks exploit spatially local correlation by enforcing a sparse local connectivity pattern between neurons of adjacent layers: each neuron is connected to only a small region of the input volume.
[src:image-super-resolution/convolutional-neural-network-p01] The extent of this connectivity is a hyperparameter called the receptive field of the neuron.
[src:image-super-resolution/convolutional-neural-network-p01] The connections are local in space (along width and height), but always extend along the entire depth of the input volume.
[src:image-super-resolution/convolutional-neural-network-p01] Such an architecture ensures that the learned filters produce the strongest response to a spatially local input pattern.
[src:image-super-resolution/convolutional-neural-network-p01] The spatial size of the output volume is a function of the input volume size W , the kernel field size K of the convolutional layer neurons, the stride S , and the amount of zero padding P on the border.
[src:image-super-resolution/convolutional-neural-network-p01] If this number is not an integer, then the strides are incorrect and the neurons cannot be tiled to fit across the input volume in a symmetric way.
[src:image-super-resolution/convolutional-neural-network-p01] In general, setting zero padding to be ${\textstyle P=(K-1)/2}$ when the stride is $S=1$ ensures that the input volume and output volume will have the same size spatially.
[src:image-super-resolution/convolutional-neural-network-p01] However, it is not always completely necessary to use all of the neurons of the previous layer.
[src:image-super-resolution/convolutional-neural-network-p01] For example, a neural network designer may decide to use just a portion of padding.
[src:image-super-resolution/convolutional-neural-network-p01] A parameter sharing scheme is used in convolutional layers to control the number of free parameters.
[src:image-super-resolution/convolutional-neural-network-p01] It relies on the assumption that if a patch feature is useful to compute at some spatial position, then it should also be useful to compute at other positions.
[src:image-super-resolution/convolutional-neural-network-p01] Denoting a single 2-dimensional slice of depth as a *depth slice*, the neurons in each depth slice are constrained to use the same weights and bias.
[src:image-super-resolution/convolutional-neural-network-p01] Since all neurons in a single depth slice share the same parameters, the forward pass in each depth slice of the convolutional layer can be computed as a convolution of the neuron's weights with the input volume.
[src:image-super-resolution/convolutional-neural-network-p01] Therefore, it is common to refer to the sets of weights as a filter (or a kernel), which is convolved with the input.
[src:image-super-resolution/convolutional-neural-network-p01] The result of this convolution is an activation map, and the set of activation maps for each different filter are stacked together along the depth dimension to produce the output volume.
[src:image-super-resolution/convolutional-neural-network-p01] Parameter sharing contributes to the translation invariance of the CNN architecture.
[src:image-super-resolution/convolutional-neural-network-p01] Sometimes, the parameter sharing assumption may not make sense.
[src:image-super-resolution/convolutional-neural-network-p01] This is especially the case when the input images to a CNN have some specific centered structure; for which we expect completely different features to be learned on different spatial locations.
[src:image-super-resolution/convolutional-neural-network-p01] One practical example is when the inputs are faces that have been centered in the image: we might expect different eye-specific or hair-specific features to be learned in different parts of the image.
[src:image-super-resolution/convolutional-neural-network-p01] In that case it is common to relax the parameter sharing scheme, and instead simply call the layer a "locally connected layer".
[src:image-super-resolution/convolutional-neural-network-p01] In this layer, the convolutional kernels' parameters are not shared.
[src:image-super-resolution/convolutional-neural-network-p01] Instead, the network learns independent weights and biases for each spatial location.
[src:image-super-resolution/convolutional-neural-network-p01] This allows each location to have its own feature-learning ability, making it better suited to handle images with distinct central structures or irregular features.
[src:image-super-resolution/convolutional-neural-network-p01] Another important concept of CNNs is pooling, which is used as a form of non-linear down-sampling.
[src:image-super-resolution/convolutional-neural-network-p01] Pooling provides downsampling because it reduces the spatial dimensions (height and width) of the input feature maps while retaining the most important information.
[src:image-super-resolution/convolutional-neural-network-p01] There are several non-linear functions to implement pooling, where *max pooling* and *average pooling* are the most common.
[src:image-super-resolution/convolutional-neural-network-p01] Pooling aggregates information from small regions of the input creating partitions of the input feature map, typically using a fixed-size window (like 2x2) and applying a stride (often 2) to move the window across the input.
[src:image-super-resolution/convolutional-neural-network-p01] Note that without using a stride greater than 1, pooling would not perform downsampling, as it would simply move the pooling window across the input one step at a time, without reducing the size of the feature map.
[src:image-super-resolution/convolutional-neural-network-p01] In other words, the stride is what actually causes the downsampling by determining how much the pooling window moves over the input.
[src:image-super-resolution/convolutional-neural-network-p01] Intuitively, the exact location of a feature is less important than its rough location relative to other features.
[src:image-super-resolution/convolutional-neural-network-p01] This is the idea behind the use of pooling in convolutional neural networks.
[src:image-super-resolution/convolutional-neural-network-p01] The pooling layer serves to progressively reduce the spatial size of the representation, to reduce the number of parameters, memory footprint and amount of computation in the network, and hence to also control overfitting.
[src:image-super-resolution/convolutional-neural-network-p01] It is common to periodically insert a pooling layer between successive convolutional layers (each one typically followed by an activation function, such as a ReLU layer) in a CNN architecture.
[src:image-super-resolution/convolutional-neural-network-p01] While pooling layers contribute to local translation invariance, they do not provide global translation invariance in a CNN, unless a form of global pooling is used.
[src:image-super-resolution/convolutional-neural-network-p01] The pooling layer commonly operates independently on every depth, or slice, of the input and resizes it spatially.
[src:image-super-resolution/convolutional-neural-network-p01] The depth dimension remains unchanged (this is true for other forms of pooling as well).
[src:image-super-resolution/convolutional-neural-network-p01] In addition to max pooling, pooling units can use other functions, such as average pooling or ℓ2-norm pooling.
[src:image-super-resolution/convolutional-neural-network-p01] Average pooling was often used historically but has recently fallen out of favor compared to max pooling, which generally performs better in practice.
[src:image-super-resolution/convolutional-neural-network-p01] Due to the effects of fast spatial reduction of the size of the representation, there is a recent trend towards using smaller filters or discarding pooling layers altogether.
[src:image-super-resolution/convolutional-neural-network-p01] A channel max pooling (CMP) operation layer conducts the MP operation along the channel side among the corresponding positions of the consecutive feature maps for the purpose of redundant information elimination.
[src:image-super-resolution/convolutional-neural-network-p01] The CMP makes the significant features gather together within fewer channels, which is important for fine-grained image classification that needs more discriminating features.
[src:image-super-resolution/convolutional-neural-network-p01] Meanwhile, another advantage of the CMP operation is to make the channel number of feature maps smaller before it connects to the first fully connected (FC) layer.
[src:image-super-resolution/convolutional-neural-network-p01] Similar to the MP operation, we denote the input feature maps and output feature maps of a CMP layer as F ∈ R(C×M×N) and C ∈ R(c×M×N), respectively, where C and c are the channel numbers of the input and output feature maps, M and N are the widths and the height of the feature maps, respectively.
[src:image-super-resolution/convolutional-neural-network-p01] Note that the CMP operation only changes the channel number of the feature maps.
[src:image-super-resolution/convolutional-neural-network-p01] The width and the height of the feature maps are not changed, which is different from the MP operation.
[src:image-super-resolution/convolutional-neural-network-p01] ReLU is the abbreviation of rectified linear unit.
[src:image-super-resolution/convolutional-neural-network-p01] It was proposed by Alston Householder in 1941, and used in CNN by Kunihiko Fukushima in 1969.
[src:image-super-resolution/convolutional-neural-network-p01] ReLU applies the non-saturating activation function ${\textstyle f(x)=\max(0,x)}$ .
[src:image-super-resolution/convolutional-neural-network-p01] It effectively removes negative values from an activation map by setting them to zero.
[src:image-super-resolution/convolutional-neural-network-p01] It introduces nonlinearity to the decision function and in the overall network without affecting the receptive fields of the convolution layers.
[src:image-super-resolution/convolutional-neural-network-p01] In 2011, Xavier Glorot, Antoine Bordes and Yoshua Bengio found that ReLU enables better training of deeper networks, compared to widely used activation functions prior to 2011.
[src:image-super-resolution/convolutional-neural-network-p01] Other functions can also be used to increase nonlinearity, for example the saturating hyperbolic tangent $f(x)=\tanh(x)$ , $f(x)=|\tanh(x)|$ , and the sigmoid function ${\textstyle \sigma (x)=(1+e^{-x})^{-1}}$ .
[src:image-super-resolution/convolutional-neural-network-p01] ReLU is often preferred to other functions because it trains the neural network several times faster without a significant penalty to generalization accuracy.
[src:image-super-resolution/convolutional-neural-network-p01] After several convolutional and max pooling layers, the final classification is done via fully connected layers.
[src:image-super-resolution/convolutional-neural-network-p01] Neurons in a fully connected layer have connections to all activations in the previous layer, as seen in regular (non-convolutional) artificial neural networks.
[src:image-super-resolution/convolutional-neural-network-p01] Their activations can thus be computed as an affine transformation, with matrix multiplication followed by a bias offset (vector addition of a learned or fixed bias term).
[src:image-super-resolution/convolutional-neural-network-p01] The "loss layer", or "loss function", exemplifies how training penalizes the deviation between the predicted output of the network, and the true data labels (during supervised learning).
[src:image-super-resolution/convolutional-neural-network-p01] Various loss functions can be used, depending on the specific task.
[src:image-super-resolution/convolutional-neural-network-p01] The Softmax loss function is used for predicting a single class of *K* mutually exclusive classes.
[src:image-super-resolution/convolutional-neural-network-p01] Sigmoid cross-entropy loss is used for predicting *K* independent probability values in $[0,1]$ .
[src:image-super-resolution/convolutional-neural-network-p01] Euclidean loss is used for regressing to real-valued labels $(-\infty ,\infty )$ .
[src:image-super-resolution/convolutional-neural-network-p01] Hyperparameters are various settings that are used to control the learning process.
[src:image-super-resolution/convolutional-neural-network-p01] CNNs use more hyperparameters than a standard multilayer perceptron (MLP).
[src:image-super-resolution/convolutional-neural-network-p01] Padding is the addition of (typically) 0-valued pixels on the borders of an image.
[src:image-super-resolution/convolutional-neural-network-p01] This is done so that the border pixels are not undervalued (lost) from the output because they would ordinarily participate in only a single receptive field instance.
[src:image-super-resolution/convolutional-neural-network-p01] The padding applied is typically one less than the corresponding kernel dimension.
[src:image-super-resolution/convolutional-neural-network-p01] For example, a convolutional layer using 3x3 kernels would receive a 2-pixel pad, that is 1 pixel on each side of the image.
[src:image-super-resolution/convolutional-neural-network-p01] The stride is the number of pixels that the analysis window moves on each iteration.
[src:image-super-resolution/convolutional-neural-network-p01] A stride of 2 means that each kernel is offset by 2 pixels from its predecessor.
[src:image-super-resolution/convolutional-neural-network-p01] Since feature map size decreases with depth, layers near the input layer tend to have fewer filters while higher layers can have more.
[src:image-super-resolution/convolutional-neural-network-p01] To equalize computation at each layer, the product of feature values *va* with pixel position is kept roughly constant across layers.
[src:image-super-resolution/convolutional-neural-network-p01] Preserving more information about the input would require keeping the total number of activations (number of feature maps times number of pixel positions) non-decreasing from one layer to the next.
[src:image-super-resolution/convolutional-neural-network-p01] The number of feature maps directly controls the capacity and depends on the number of available examples and task complexity.
[src:image-super-resolution/convolutional-neural-network-p01] Common filter sizes found in the literature vary greatly, and are usually chosen based on the data set.
[src:image-super-resolution/convolutional-neural-network-p01] Typical filter sizes range from 1x1 to 7x7.
[src:image-super-resolution/convolutional-neural-network-p01] As two famous examples, AlexNet used 3x3, 5x5, and 11x11.
[src:image-super-resolution/convolutional-neural-network-p01] The challenge is to find the right level of granularity so as to create abstractions at the proper scale, given a particular data set, and without overfitting.
[src:image-super-resolution/convolutional-neural-network-p01] Max pooling is typically used, often with a 2x2 dimension.
[src:image-super-resolution/convolutional-neural-network-p01] This implies that the input is drastically downsampled, reducing processing cost.
[src:image-super-resolution/convolutional-neural-network-p01] Greater pooling reduces the dimension of the signal, and may result in unacceptable information loss.
[src:image-super-resolution/convolutional-neural-network-p01] Often, non-overlapping pooling windows perform best.
[src:image-super-resolution/convolutional-neural-network-p01] Dilation involves ignoring pixels within a kernel.
[src:image-super-resolution/convolutional-neural-network-p01] This reduces processing memory potentially without significant signal loss.
[src:image-super-resolution/convolutional-neural-network-p01] A dilation of 2 on a 3x3 kernel expands the kernel to 5x5, while still processing 9 (evenly spaced) pixels.
[src:image-super-resolution/convolutional-neural-network-p01] Accordingly, dilation of 4 expands the kernel to 7x7.
[src:image-super-resolution/convolutional-neural-network-p01] It is commonly assumed that CNNs are invariant to shifts of the input.
[src:image-super-resolution/convolutional-neural-network-p01] Convolution or pooling layers within a CNN that do not have a stride greater than one are indeed equivariant to translations of the input.
[src:image-super-resolution/convolutional-neural-network-p01] Furthermore, if a CNN makes use of fully connected layers, translation equivariance does not imply translation invariance, as the fully connected layers are not invariant to shifts of the input.
[src:image-super-resolution/convolutional-neural-network-p01] One solution for complete translation invariance is avoiding any down-sampling throughout the network and applying global average pooling at the last layer.
[src:image-super-resolution/convolutional-neural-network-p01] Additionally, several other partial solutions have been proposed, such as anti-aliasing before downsampling operations, spatial transformer networks, data augmentation, subsampling combined with pooling, and capsule neural networks.
[src:image-super-resolution/convolutional-neural-network-p01] The accuracy of the final model is typically estimated on a sub-part of the dataset set apart at the start, often called a test set.
[src:image-super-resolution/convolutional-neural-network-p01] Alternatively, methods such as *k*-fold cross-validation are applied.
[src:image-super-resolution/convolutional-neural-network-p01] Other strategies include using conformal prediction.
[src:image-super-resolution/convolutional-neural-network-p01] Regularization is a process of introducing additional information to solve an ill-posed problem or to prevent overfitting.
[src:image-super-resolution/convolutional-neural-network-p01] CNNs use various types of regularization.
[src:image-super-resolution/convolutional-neural-network-p01] Because networks have so many parameters, they are prone to overfitting.
[src:image-super-resolution/convolutional-neural-network-p01] One method to reduce overfitting is dropout, introduced in 2014.
[src:image-super-resolution/convolutional-neural-network-p01] At each training stage, individual nodes are either "dropped out" of the net (ignored) with probability $1-p$ or kept with probability p , so that a reduced network is left; incoming and outgoing edges to a dropped-out node are also removed.
[src:image-super-resolution/convolutional-neural-network-p01] Only the reduced network is trained on the data in that stage.
[src:image-super-resolution/convolutional-neural-network-p01] The removed nodes are then reinserted into the network with their original weights.
[src:image-super-resolution/convolutional-neural-network-p01] In the training stages, p is usually 0.5; for input nodes, it is typically much higher because information is directly lost when input nodes are ignored.
[src:image-super-resolution/convolutional-neural-network-p01] At testing time after training has finished, we would ideally like to find a sample average of all possible $2^{n}$ dropped-out networks; unfortunately this is unfeasible for large values of n .
[src:image-super-resolution/convolutional-neural-network-p01] However, we can find an approximation by using the full network with each node's output weighted by a factor of p , so the expected value of the output of any node is the same as in the training stages.
[src:image-super-resolution/convolutional-neural-network-p01] This is the biggest contribution of the dropout method: although it effectively generates $2^{n}$ neural nets, and as such allows for model combination, at test time only a single network needs to be tested.
[src:image-super-resolution/convolutional-neural-network-p01] By avoiding training all nodes on all training data, dropout decreases overfitting.
[src:image-super-resolution/convolutional-neural-network-p01] The method also significantly improves training speed.
[src:image-super-resolution/convolutional-neural-network-p01] This makes the model combination practical, even for deep neural networks.
[src:image-super-resolution/convolutional-neural-network-p01] The technique seems to reduce node interactions, leading them to learn more robust features that better generalize to new data.
[src:image-super-resolution/convolutional-neural-network-p01] DropConnect is the generalization of dropout in which each connection, rather than each output unit, can be dropped with probability $1-p$ .
[src:image-super-resolution/convolutional-neural-network-p01] Each unit thus receives input from a random subset of units in the previous layer.
[src:image-super-resolution/convolutional-neural-network-p01] DropConnect is similar to dropout as it introduces dynamic sparsity within the model, but differs in that the sparsity is on the weights, rather than the output vectors of a layer.
[src:image-super-resolution/convolutional-neural-network-p01] In other words, the fully connected layer with DropConnect becomes a sparsely connected layer in which the connections are chosen at random during the training stage.
[src:image-super-resolution/convolutional-neural-network-p01] A major drawback to dropout is that it does not have the same benefits for convolutional layers, where the neurons are not fully connected.
[src:image-super-resolution/convolutional-neural-network-p01] This approach is free of hyperparameters and can be combined with other regularization approaches, such as dropout and data augmentation.
[src:image-super-resolution/convolutional-neural-network-p01] An alternate view of stochastic pooling is that it is equivalent to standard max pooling but with many copies of an input image, each having small local deformations.
[src:image-super-resolution/convolutional-neural-network-p01] This is similar to explicit elastic deformations of the input images, which delivers excellent performance on the MNIST data set.
[src:image-super-resolution/convolutional-neural-network-p01] Using stochastic pooling in a multilayer model gives an exponential number of deformations since the selections in higher layers are independent of those below.
[src:image-super-resolution/convolutional-neural-network-p01] Because the degree of model overfitting is determined by both its power and the amount of training it receives, providing a convolutional network with more training examples can reduce overfitting.
[src:image-super-resolution/convolutional-neural-network-p01] Because there is often not enough available data to train, especially considering that some part should be spared for later testing, two approaches are to either generate new data from scratch (if possible) or perturb existing data to create new ones.
[src:image-super-resolution/convolutional-neural-network-p01] For example, input images can be cropped, rotated, or rescaled to create new examples with the same labels as the original training set.
[src:image-super-resolution/convolutional-neural-network-p01] One of the simplest methods to prevent overfitting of a network is to simply stop the training before overfitting has had a chance to occur.
[src:image-super-resolution/convolutional-neural-network-p01] It comes with the disadvantage that the learning process is halted.
[src:image-super-resolution/convolutional-neural-network-p01] Another simple way to prevent overfitting is to limit the number of parameters, typically by limiting the number of hidden units in each layer or limiting network depth.
[src:image-super-resolution/convolutional-neural-network-p01] For convolutional networks, the filter size also affects the number of parameters.
[src:image-super-resolution/convolutional-neural-network-p01] Limiting the number of parameters restricts the predictive power of the network directly, reducing the complexity of the function that it can perform on the data, and thus limits the amount of overfitting.
[src:image-super-resolution/convolutional-neural-network-p01] A simple form of added regularizer is weight decay, which simply adds an additional error, proportional to the sum of weights (L1 norm) or squared magnitude (L2 norm) of the weight vector, to the error at each node.
[src:image-super-resolution/convolutional-neural-network-p01] The level of acceptable model complexity can be reduced by increasing the proportionality constant('alpha' hyperparameter), thus increasing the penalty for large weight vectors.
[src:image-super-resolution/convolutional-neural-network-p01] L2 regularization is the most common form of regularization.
[src:image-super-resolution/convolutional-neural-network-p01] It can be implemented by penalizing the squared magnitude of all parameters directly in the objective.
[src:image-super-resolution/convolutional-neural-network-p01] The L2 regularization has the intuitive interpretation of heavily penalizing peaky weight vectors and preferring diffuse weight vectors.
[src:image-super-resolution/convolutional-neural-network-p01] Due to multiplicative interactions between weights and inputs this has the useful property of encouraging the network to use all of its inputs a little rather than some of its inputs a lot.
[src:image-super-resolution/convolutional-neural-network-p01] It makes the weight vectors sparse during optimization.
[src:image-super-resolution/convolutional-neural-network-p01] In other words, neurons with L1 regularization end up using only a sparse subset of their most important inputs and become nearly invariant to the noisy inputs.
[src:image-super-resolution/convolutional-neural-network-p01] L1 with L2 regularization can be combined; this is called elastic net regularization.
[src:image-super-resolution/convolutional-neural-network-p01] Another form of regularization is to enforce an absolute upper bound on the magnitude of the weight vector for every neuron and use projected gradient descent to enforce the constraint.
[src:image-super-resolution/convolutional-neural-network-p01] In practice, this corresponds to performing the parameter update as normal, and then enforcing the constraint by clamping the weight vector ${\vec {w}}$ of every neuron to satisfy $\|{\vec {w}}\|_{2}<c$ .
[src:image-super-resolution/convolutional-neural-network-p01] Some papers report improvements when using this form of regularization.
[src:image-super-resolution/convolutional-neural-network-p02] Pooling loses the precise spatial relationships between high-level parts (such as nose and mouth in a face image).
[src:image-super-resolution/convolutional-neural-network-p02] These relationships are needed for identity recognition.
[src:image-super-resolution/convolutional-neural-network-p02] Overlapping the pools so that each feature occurs in multiple pools, helps retain the information.
[src:image-super-resolution/convolutional-neural-network-p02] Translation alone cannot extrapolate the understanding of geometric relationships to a radically new viewpoint, such as a different orientation or scale.
[src:image-super-resolution/convolutional-neural-network-p02] On the other hand, people are very good at extrapolating; after seeing a new shape once they can recognize it from a different viewpoint.
[src:image-super-resolution/convolutional-neural-network-p02] An earlier common way to deal with this problem is to train the network on transformed data in different orientations, scales, lighting, etc. so that the network can cope with these variations.
[src:image-super-resolution/convolutional-neural-network-p02] This is computationally intensive for large data-sets.
[src:image-super-resolution/convolutional-neural-network-p02] The alternative is to use a hierarchy of coordinate frames and use a group of neurons to represent a conjunction of the shape of the feature and its pose relative to the retina.
[src:image-super-resolution/convolutional-neural-network-p02] The pose relative to the retina is the relationship between the coordinate frame of the retina and the intrinsic features' coordinate frame.
[src:image-super-resolution/convolutional-neural-network-p02] Thus, one way to represent something is to embed the coordinate frame within it.
[src:image-super-resolution/convolutional-neural-network-p02] This allows large features to be recognized by using the consistency of the poses of their parts (e.g. nose and mouth poses make a consistent prediction of the pose of the whole face).
[src:image-super-resolution/convolutional-neural-network-p02] This approach ensures that the higher-level entity (e.g. face) is present when the lower-level (e.g. nose and mouth) agree on its prediction of the pose.
[src:image-super-resolution/convolutional-neural-network-p02] The vectors of neuronal activity that represent pose ("pose vectors") allow spatial transformations modeled as linear operations that make it easier for the network to learn the hierarchy of visual entities and generalize across viewpoints.
[src:image-super-resolution/convolutional-neural-network-p02] This is similar to the way the human visual system imposes coordinate frames in order to represent shapes.
[src:image-super-resolution/convolutional-neural-network-p02] CNNs are often used in image recognition systems.
[src:image-super-resolution/convolutional-neural-network-p02] In 2012, an error rate of 0.23% on the MNIST database was reported.
[src:image-super-resolution/convolutional-neural-network-p02] Another paper on using CNN for image classification reported that the learning process was "surprisingly fast"; in the same paper, the best published results as of 2011 were achieved in the MNIST database and the NORB database.
[src:image-super-resolution/convolutional-neural-network-p02] Subsequently, a similar CNN called AlexNet won the ImageNet Large Scale Visual Recognition Challenge 2012.
[src:image-super-resolution/convolutional-neural-network-p02] When applied to facial recognition, CNNs achieved a large decrease in error rate.
[src:image-super-resolution/convolutional-neural-network-p02] Another paper reported a 97.6% recognition rate on "5,600 still images of more than 10 subjects".
[src:image-super-resolution/convolutional-neural-network-p02] CNNs were used to assess video quality in an objective way after manual training; the resulting system had a very low root mean square error.
[src:image-super-resolution/convolutional-neural-network-p02] The ImageNet Large Scale Visual Recognition Challenge is a benchmark in object classification and detection, with millions of images and hundreds of object classes.
[src:image-super-resolution/convolutional-neural-network-p02] In the ILSVRC 2014, a large-scale visual recognition challenge, almost every highly ranked team used CNN as their basic framework.
[src:image-super-resolution/convolutional-neural-network-p02] The winner GoogLeNet (the foundation of DeepDream) increased the mean average precision of object detection to 0.439329, and reduced classification error to 0.06656, the best result to date.
[src:image-super-resolution/convolutional-neural-network-p02] Its network applied more than 30 layers.
[src:image-super-resolution/convolutional-neural-network-p02] That performance of convolutional neural networks on the ImageNet tests was close to that of humans.
[src:image-super-resolution/convolutional-neural-network-p02] The best algorithms still struggle with objects that are small or thin, such as a small ant on a stem of a flower or a person holding a quill in their hand.
[src:image-super-resolution/convolutional-neural-network-p02] They also have trouble with images that have been distorted with filters, an increasingly common phenomenon with modern digital cameras.
[src:image-super-resolution/convolutional-neural-network-p02] By contrast, those kinds of images rarely trouble humans.
[src:image-super-resolution/convolutional-neural-network-p02] Humans, however, tend to have trouble with other issues.
[src:image-super-resolution/convolutional-neural-network-p02] For example, they are not good at classifying objects into fine-grained categories such as the particular breed of dog or species of bird, whereas convolutional neural networks handle this.
[src:image-super-resolution/convolutional-neural-network-p02] In 2015, a many-layered CNN demonstrated the ability to spot faces from a wide range of angles, including upside down, even when partially occluded, with competitive performance.
[src:image-super-resolution/convolutional-neural-network-p02] The network was trained on a database of 200,000 images that included faces at various angles and orientations and a further 20 million images without faces.
[src:image-super-resolution/convolutional-neural-network-p02] They used batches of 128 images over 50,000 iterations.
[src:image-super-resolution/convolutional-neural-network-p02] Compared to image data domains, there is relatively little work on applying CNNs to video classification.
[src:image-super-resolution/convolutional-neural-network-p02] Video is more complex than images since it has another (temporal) dimension.
[src:image-super-resolution/convolutional-neural-network-p02] However, some extensions of CNNs into the video domain have been explored.
[src:image-super-resolution/convolutional-neural-network-p02] One approach is to treat space and time as equivalent dimensions of the input and perform convolutions in both time and space.
[src:image-super-resolution/convolutional-neural-network-p02] Another way is to fuse the features of two convolutional neural networks, one for the spatial and one for the temporal stream.
[src:image-super-resolution/convolutional-neural-network-p02] Long short-term memory (LSTM) recurrent units are typically incorporated after the CNN to account for inter-frame or inter-clip dependencies.
[src:image-super-resolution/convolutional-neural-network-p02] Unsupervised learning schemes for training spatio-temporal features have been introduced, based on convolutional gated restricted Boltzmann machines and independent subspace analysis.
[src:image-super-resolution/convolutional-neural-network-p02] Its application can be seen in text-to-video models.
[src:image-super-resolution/convolutional-neural-network-p02] CNNs have also been explored for natural language processing.
[src:image-super-resolution/convolutional-neural-network-p02] CNN models are effective for various NLP problems and achieved excellent results in semantic parsing, search query retrieval, sentence modeling, classification, prediction and other traditional NLP tasks.
[src:image-super-resolution/convolutional-neural-network-p02] Compared to traditional language processing methods such as recurrent neural networks, CNNs can represent different contextual realities of language that do not rely on a series-sequence assumption, while RNNs are better suitable when classical time series modeling is required.
[src:image-super-resolution/convolutional-neural-network-p02] CNNs have been applied in ecological and behavioral research to automatically detect and quantify animal behavior from visual data, enabling identification of animals, tracking of individuals, estimation of pose, and classification of specific actions such as feeding, and social interactions.
[src:image-super-resolution/convolutional-neural-network-p02] Combined with multi-object tracking and temporal modeling, these systems can extract behavioral sequences over extended recordings, reducing reliance on manual annotation and increasing throughput for studies of individual variation, social networks, and collective dynamics.
[src:image-super-resolution/convolutional-neural-network-p02] A CNN with 1-D convolutions was used on time series in the frequency domain (spectral residual) by an unsupervised model to detect anomalies in the time domain.
[src:image-super-resolution/convolutional-neural-network-p02] Predicting the interaction between molecules and biological proteins can identify potential treatments.
[src:image-super-resolution/convolutional-neural-network-p02] In 2015, Atomwise introduced AtomNet, the first deep learning neural network for structure-based drug design.
[src:image-super-resolution/convolutional-neural-network-p02] The system trains directly on 3-dimensional representations of chemical interactions.
[src:image-super-resolution/convolutional-neural-network-p02] Similar to how image recognition networks learn to compose smaller, spatially proximate features into larger, complex structures, AtomNet discovers chemical features, such as aromaticity, sp3 carbons, and hydrogen bonding.
[src:image-super-resolution/convolutional-neural-network-p02] Subsequently, AtomNet was used to predict novel candidate biomolecules for multiple disease targets, most notably treatments for the Ebola virus and multiple sclerosis.
[src:image-super-resolution/convolutional-neural-network-p02] CNNs have been used in the game of checkers.
[src:image-super-resolution/convolutional-neural-network-p02] From 1999 to 2001, Fogel and Chellapilla published papers showing how a convolutional neural network could learn to play checkers using co-evolution.
[src:image-super-resolution/convolutional-neural-network-p02] The learning process did not use prior human professional games, but rather focused on a minimal set of information contained in the checkerboard: the location and type of pieces, and the difference in number of pieces between the two sides.
[src:image-super-resolution/convolutional-neural-network-p02] Ultimately, the program (Blondie24) was tested on 165 games against players and ranked in the highest 0.4%.
[src:image-super-resolution/convolutional-neural-network-p02] It also earned a win against the program Chinook at its "expert" level of play.
[src:image-super-resolution/convolutional-neural-network-p02] In December 2014, Clark and Storkey published a paper showing that a CNN trained by supervised learning from a database of human professional games could outperform GNU Go and win some games against Monte Carlo tree search Fuego 1.1 in a fraction of the time it took Fuego to play.
[src:image-super-resolution/convolutional-neural-network-p02] Later it was announced that a large 12-layer convolutional neural network had correctly predicted the professional move in 55% of positions, equalling the accuracy of a 6 dan human player.
[src:image-super-resolution/convolutional-neural-network-p02] A couple of CNNs for choosing moves to try ("policy network") and evaluating positions ("value network") driving MCTS were used by AlphaGo, the first to beat the best human player at the time.
[src:image-super-resolution/convolutional-neural-network-p02] Recurrent neural networks are generally considered the best neural network architectures for time series forecasting (and sequence modeling in general), but recent studies show that convolutional networks can perform comparably or even better.
[src:image-super-resolution/convolutional-neural-network-p02] Dilated convolutions might enable one-dimensional convolutional neural networks to effectively learn time series dependences.
[src:image-super-resolution/convolutional-neural-network-p02] Convolutions can be implemented more efficiently than RNN-based solutions, and they do not suffer from vanishing (or exploding) gradients.
[src:image-super-resolution/convolutional-neural-network-p02] Convolutional networks can provide an improved forecasting performance when there are multiple similar time series to learn from.
[src:image-super-resolution/convolutional-neural-network-p02] CNNs can also be applied to further tasks in time series analysis (e.g., time series classification or quantile forecasting).
[src:image-super-resolution/convolutional-neural-network-p02] As archaeological findings such as clay tablets with cuneiform writing are increasingly acquired using 3D scanners, benchmark datasets are becoming available, including *HeiCuBeDa* providing almost 2000 normalized 2-D and 3-D datasets prepared with the GigaMesh Software Framework.
[src:image-super-resolution/convolutional-neural-network-p02] So curvature-based measures are used in conjunction with geometric neural networks (GNNs), e.g. for period classification of those clay tablets being among the oldest documents of human history.
[src:image-super-resolution/convolutional-neural-network-p02] For many applications, training data is not very available.
[src:image-super-resolution/convolutional-neural-network-p02] Convolutional neural networks usually require a large amount of training data in order to avoid overfitting.
[src:image-super-resolution/convolutional-neural-network-p02] A common technique is to train the network on a larger data set from a related domain.
[src:image-super-resolution/convolutional-neural-network-p02] Once the network parameters have converged an additional training step is performed using the in-domain data to fine-tune the network weights, this is known as transfer learning.
[src:image-super-resolution/convolutional-neural-network-p02] Furthermore, this technique allows convolutional network architectures to successfully be applied to problems with tiny training sets.
[src:image-super-resolution/convolutional-neural-network-p02] End-to-end training and prediction are common practice in computer vision.
[src:image-super-resolution/convolutional-neural-network-p02] However, human interpretable explanations are required for critical systems such as self-driving cars.
[src:image-super-resolution/convolutional-neural-network-p02] With recent advances in visual salience, spatial attention, and temporal attention, the most critical spatial regions/temporal instants could be visualized to justify the CNN predictions.
[src:image-super-resolution/convolutional-neural-network-p02] A deep Q-network (DQN) is a type of deep learning model that combines a deep neural network with Q-learning, a form of reinforcement learning.
[src:image-super-resolution/convolutional-neural-network-p02] Unlike earlier reinforcement learning agents, DQNs that utilize CNNs can learn directly from high-dimensional sensory inputs via reinforcement learning.
[src:image-super-resolution/convolutional-neural-network-p02] Preliminary results were presented in 2014, with an accompanying paper in February 2015.
[src:image-super-resolution/convolutional-neural-network-p02] The research described an application to Atari 2600 gaming.
[src:image-super-resolution/convolutional-neural-network-p02] Other deep reinforcement learning models preceded it.
[src:image-super-resolution/convolutional-neural-network-p02] Convolutional deep belief networks (CDBN) have structure very similar to convolutional neural networks and are trained similarly to deep belief networks.
[src:image-super-resolution/convolutional-neural-network-p02] Therefore, they exploit the 2D structure of images, like CNNs do, and make use of pre-training like deep belief networks.
[src:image-super-resolution/convolutional-neural-network-p02] They provide a generic structure that can be used in many image and signal processing tasks.
[src:image-super-resolution/convolutional-neural-network-p02] Benchmark results on standard image datasets like CIFAR have been obtained using CDBNs.
[src:image-super-resolution/convolutional-neural-network-p02] The feed-forward architecture of convolutional neural networks was extended in the neural abstraction pyramid by lateral and feedback connections.
[src:image-super-resolution/convolutional-neural-network-p02] The resulting recurrent convolutional network allows for the flexible incorporation of contextual information to iteratively resolve local ambiguities.
[src:image-super-resolution/convolutional-neural-network-p02] In contrast to previous models, image-like outputs at the highest resolution were generated, e.g., for semantic segmentation, image reconstruction, and object localization tasks.
[src:image-super-resolution/digital-image-processing] The purpose of early image processing was to improve the quality of the image.
[src:image-super-resolution/digital-image-processing] In image processing, the input is a low-quality image, and the output is an image with improved quality.
[src:image-super-resolution/digital-image-processing] Common image processing includes image enhancement, restoration, encoding, and compression.
[src:image-super-resolution/digital-image-processing] The first successful application was the American Jet Propulsion Laboratory (JPL).
[src:image-super-resolution/digital-image-processing] They used image processing techniques such as geometric correction, gradation transformation, noise removal, etc. on the thousands of lunar photos sent back by the Space Detector Ranger 7 in 1964, taking into account the position of the Sun and the environment of the Moon.
[src:image-super-resolution/digital-image-processing] The impact of the successful mapping of the Moon's surface map by the computer has been a success.
[src:image-super-resolution/digital-image-processing] Later, more complex image processing was performed on the nearly 100,000 photos sent back by the spacecraft, so that the topographic map, color map and panoramic mosaic of the Moon were obtained, which achieved extraordinary results and laid a solid foundation for human landing on the Moon.
[src:image-super-resolution/digital-image-processing] The cost of processing was fairly high, however, with the computing equipment of that era.
[src:image-super-resolution/digital-image-processing] That changed in the 1970s, when digital image processing proliferated as cheaper computers and dedicated hardware became available.
[src:image-super-resolution/digital-image-processing] This led to images being processed in real-time, for some dedicated problems such as television standards conversion.
[src:image-super-resolution/digital-image-processing] As general-purpose computers became faster, they started to take over the role of dedicated hardware for all but the most specialized and computer-intensive operations.
[src:image-super-resolution/digital-image-processing] With the fast computers and signal processors available in the 2000s, digital image processing has become the most common form of image processing, and is generally used because it is not only the most versatile method, but also the cheapest.
[src:image-super-resolution/digital-image-processing] The basis for modern image sensors is metal–oxide–semiconductor (MOS) technology, invented at Bell Labs between 1955 and 1960, This led to the development of digital semiconductor image sensors, including the charge-coupled device (CCD) and later the CMOS sensor.
[src:image-super-resolution/digital-image-processing] The charge-coupled device was invented by Willard S.
[src:image-super-resolution/digital-image-processing] While researching MOS technology, they realized that an electric charge was the analogy of the magnetic bubble and that it could be stored on a tiny MOS capacitor.
[src:image-super-resolution/digital-image-processing] As it was fairly straightforward to fabricate a series of MOS capacitors in a row, they connected a suitable voltage to them so that the charge could be stepped along from one to the next.
[src:image-super-resolution/digital-image-processing] The CCD is a semiconductor circuit that was later used in the first digital video cameras for television broadcasting.
[src:image-super-resolution/digital-image-processing] The NMOS active-pixel sensor (APS) was invented by Olympus in Japan during the mid-1980s.
[src:image-super-resolution/digital-image-processing] This was enabled by advances in MOS semiconductor device fabrication, with MOSFET scaling reaching smaller micron and then sub-micron levels.
[src:image-super-resolution/digital-image-processing] The NMOS APS was fabricated by Tsutomu Nakamura's team at Olympus in 1985.
[src:image-super-resolution/digital-image-processing] The CMOS active-pixel sensor (CMOS sensor) was later developed by Eric Fossum's team at the NASA Jet Propulsion Laboratory in 1993.
[src:image-super-resolution/digital-image-processing] By 2007, sales of CMOS sensors had surpassed CCD sensors.
[src:image-super-resolution/digital-image-processing] MOS image sensors are widely used in optical mouse technology.
[src:image-super-resolution/digital-image-processing] The first optical mouse, invented by Richard F.
[src:image-super-resolution/digital-image-processing] Lyon at Xerox in 1980, used a 5 μm NMOS integrated circuit sensor chip.
[src:image-super-resolution/digital-image-processing] Since the first commercial optical mouse, the IntelliMouse introduced in 1999, most optical mouse devices use CMOS sensors.
[src:image-super-resolution/digital-image-processing] An important development in digital image compression technology was the discrete cosine transform (DCT), a lossy compression technique first proposed by Nasir Ahmed in 1972.
[src:image-super-resolution/digital-image-processing] DCT compression became the basis for JPEG, which was introduced by the Joint Photographic Experts Group in 1992.
[src:image-super-resolution/digital-image-processing] JPEG compresses images down to much smaller file sizes, and has become the most widely used image file format on the Internet.
[src:image-super-resolution/digital-image-processing] Its highly efficient DCT compression algorithm was largely responsible for the wide proliferation of digital images and digital photos, with several billion JPEG images produced every day as of 2015.
[src:image-super-resolution/digital-image-processing] Medical imaging techniques produce very large amounts of data, especially from CT, MRI and PET modalities.
[src:image-super-resolution/digital-image-processing] As a result, storage and communications of electronic image data are prohibitive without the use of compression.
[src:image-super-resolution/digital-image-processing] JPEG 2000 image compression is used by the DICOM standard for storage and transmission of medical images.
[src:image-super-resolution/digital-image-processing] The cost and feasibility of accessing large image data sets over low or various bandwidths are further addressed by use of another DICOM standard, called JPIP, to enable efficient streaming of the JPEG 2000 compressed image data.
[src:image-super-resolution/digital-image-processing] Electronic signal processing was revolutionized by the wide adoption of MOS technology in the 1970s.
[src:image-super-resolution/digital-image-processing] MOS integrated circuit technology was the basis for the first single-chip microprocessors and microcontrollers in the early 1970s, and then the first single-chip digital signal processor (DSP) chips in the late 1970s.
[src:image-super-resolution/digital-image-processing] DSP chips have since been widely used in digital image processing.
[src:image-super-resolution/digital-image-processing] The discrete cosine transform (DCT) image compression algorithm has been widely implemented in DSP chips, with many companies developing DSP chips based on DCT technology.
[src:image-super-resolution/digital-image-processing] DCTs are widely used for encoding, decoding, video coding, audio coding, multiplexing, control signals, signaling, analog-to-digital conversion, formatting luminance and color differences, and color formats such as YUV444 and YUV411.
[src:image-super-resolution/digital-image-processing] DCTs are also commonly used for high-definition television (HDTV) encoder/decoder chips.
[src:image-super-resolution/digital-image-processing] Digital image processing allows the use of much more complex algorithms, and hence, can offer both more sophisticated performance at simple tasks, and the implementation of methods which would be impossible by analogue means.
[src:image-super-resolution/digital-image-processing] Digital filters are used to blur and sharpen digital images.
[src:image-super-resolution/digital-image-processing] Notice that the highpass filter shows extra edges when zero padded compared to the repeated edge padding.
[src:image-super-resolution/digital-image-processing] MATLAB example for spatial domain highpass filtering.
[src:image-super-resolution/digital-image-processing] To apply the affine matrix to an image, the image is converted to a matrix in which each entry corresponds to the pixel intensity at that location.
[src:image-super-resolution/digital-image-processing] Then each pixel's location can be represented as a vector indicating the coordinates of that pixel in the image, [*x*, *y*], where *x* and *y* are the row and column of a pixel in the image matrix.
[src:image-super-resolution/digital-image-processing] This allows the coordinate to be multiplied by an affine-transformation matrix, which gives the position that the pixel value will be copied to in the output image.
[src:image-super-resolution/digital-image-processing] However, to allow transformations that require translation transformations, 3-dimensional homogeneous coordinates are needed.
[src:image-super-resolution/digital-image-processing] The third dimension is usually set to a non-zero constant, usually 1, so that the new coordinate is [*x*, *y*, 1].
[src:image-super-resolution/digital-image-processing] This allows the coordinate vector to be multiplied by a 3×3 matrix, enabling translation shifts.
[src:image-super-resolution/digital-image-processing] Thus, the third dimension, i.e., the constant 1, allows translation.
[src:image-super-resolution/digital-image-processing] Because matrix multiplication is associative, multiple affine transformations can be combined into a single affine transformation by multiplying the matrix of each individual transformation in the order that the transformations are done.
[src:image-super-resolution/digital-image-processing] This results in a single matrix that, when applied to a point vector, gives the same result as all the individual transformations performed on the vector [*x*, *y*, 1] in sequence.
[src:image-super-resolution/digital-image-processing] Thus, a sequence of affine transformation matrices can be reduced to a single affine transformation matrix.
[src:image-super-resolution/digital-image-processing] For example, 2-dimensional coordinates only permit rotation about the origin (0, 0).
[src:image-super-resolution/digital-image-processing] But 3-dimensional homogeneous coordinates can be used to first translate any point to (0, 0), then perform the rotation, and lastly translate the origin (0, 0) back to the original point (the opposite of the first translation).
[src:image-super-resolution/digital-image-processing] These three affine transformations can be combined into a single matrix, thus allowing rotation around any point in the image.
[src:image-super-resolution/digital-image-processing] Mathematical morphology (MM) is a nonlinear image processing framework that analyzes shapes within images by probing local pixel neighborhoods using a small, predefined function called a structuring element.
[src:image-super-resolution/digital-image-processing] In the context of grayscale images, MM is especially useful for denoising through dilation and erosion—primitive operators that can be combined to build more complex filters.
[src:image-super-resolution/digital-image-processing] Here, ${\mathcal {S}}$ defines the neighborhood of relative coordinates $(m,n)$ over which local operations are computed.
[src:image-super-resolution/digital-image-processing] The values of $B(m,n)$ bias the image during dilation and erosion.
[src:image-super-resolution/digital-image-processing] MM operations, such as opening and closing, are composite processes that utilize both dilation and erosion to modify the structure of an image.
[src:image-super-resolution/digital-image-processing] These operations are particularly useful for tasks such as noise removal, shape smoothing, and object separation.
[src:image-super-resolution/digital-image-processing] For example, applying opening to an image f with a structuring element B would first reduce small details (through erosion) and then restore the main shapes (through dilation).
[src:image-super-resolution/digital-image-processing] This ensures that unwanted noise is removed without significantly altering the size or shape of larger objects.
[src:image-super-resolution/digital-image-processing] For instance, applying closing to the same image f would fill in small gaps within objects, such as connecting breaks in thin lines or closing small holes, while ensuring that the surrounding areas are not significantly affected.
[src:image-super-resolution/digital-image-processing] Both opening and closing can be visualized as ways of refining the structure of an image: opening simplifies and removes small, unnecessary details, while closing consolidates and connects objects to form more cohesive structures.
[src:image-super-resolution/digital-image-processing] Digital cameras generally include specialized digital image processing hardware – either dedicated chips or added circuitry on other chips – to convert the raw data from their image sensor into a color-corrected image in a standard image file format.
[src:image-super-resolution/digital-image-processing] Additional post-processing techniques increase edge sharpness or color saturation to create more naturally looking images.
[src:image-super-resolution/digital-image-processing] Face detection can be implemented with mathematical morphology, the discrete cosine transform (DCT), and horizontal projection.
[src:image-super-resolution/digital-image-processing] The feature-based method of face detection uses skin tone, edge detection, face shape, and features of a face (like eyes, mouth, etc.) to achieve face detection.
[src:image-super-resolution/digital-image-processing] The skin tone, face shape, and all the unique elements that only the human face has can be described as features.
[src:image-super-resolution/digital-image-processing] Normally, HSV or RGB color spaces are suitable for the skin filter.
[src:image-super-resolution/digital-image-processing] After filtering images with skin tone, to get the face edge, morphology and DCT are used to remove noise and fill up missing skin areas.
[src:image-super-resolution/digital-image-processing] DCT is to avoid the object with skin-like tone.
[src:image-super-resolution/digital-image-processing] Since human faces always have higher texture.
[src:image-super-resolution/digital-image-processing] Sobel operator or other operators can be applied to detect face edge.
[src:image-super-resolution/digital-image-processing] To position human features like eyes, using the projection and finding the peak of the histogram of projection helps to get the detailed features like mouth, hair, and lip.
[src:image-super-resolution/digital-image-processing] Image quality can be influenced by camera vibration, over-exposure, gray level distribution too centralized, and noise, etc.
[src:image-super-resolution/digital-image-processing] For example, the noise problem can be solved by smoothing method, while the gray level distribution problem can be improved by histogram equalization.
[src:image-super-resolution/digital-image-processing] In drawing, if there is some dissatisfied color, taking some color around the dissatisfied color and averaging them.
[src:image-super-resolution/digital-image-processing] The smoothing method can be implemented with a mask and convolution.
[src:image-super-resolution/digital-image-processing] Take the small image and mask, for instance, as below.
[src:image-super-resolution/digital-image-processing] The original image pixel is 1, 4, 28, 30.
[src:image-super-resolution/digital-image-processing] After the smoothing mask, the pixel becomes 9, 10, 9, 9, respectively.
[src:image-super-resolution/digital-image-processing] Generally, given a gray level histogram from an image as below.
[src:image-super-resolution/digital-image-processing] Changing the histogram to a uniform distribution from an image is usually what we call histogram equalization.
[src:image-super-resolution/digital-image-processing] In discrete time, the area of gray level histogram is $\sum _{i=0}^{k}H(p_{i})$ (see figure 1) while the area of uniform distribution is $\sum _{i=0}^{k}G(q_{i})$ (see figure 2).
[src:image-super-resolution/digital-image-processing] Moreover, based on the definition of a function, the Gray level histogram method is like finding a function f that satisfies f(p)=q.
[src:image-super-resolution/digital-image-processing] **Variability in image quality**: Variations in image quality and resolution, including blurry images and incomplete details, can hinder uniform processing across a database.
[src:image-super-resolution/digital-image-processing] **Object detection and Recognition**: Identifying and recognising objects within images, especially in complex scenarios with multiple objects and occlusions, poses a significant challenge.
[src:image-super-resolution/digital-image-processing] **Data annotation and labelling**: Labelling diverse and multiple images for machine recognition is crucial for further processing accuracy, as incorrect identification can lead to unrealistic results.
[src:image-super-resolution/digital-image-processing] **Computational resource intensity**: Accessing adequate computational resources for image processing can be challenging and costly, hindering progress without sufficient resources.
[src:image-super-resolution/generative-adversarial-network-p01] A **generative adversarial network** (**GAN**) is a class of machine learning frameworks and a prominent framework for approaching generative artificial intelligence.
[src:image-super-resolution/generative-adversarial-network-p01] The concept was initially developed by Ian Goodfellow and his colleagues in June 2014.
[src:image-super-resolution/generative-adversarial-network-p01] In a GAN, two neural networks compete with each other in the form of a zero-sum game, where one agent's gain is another agent's loss.
[src:image-super-resolution/generative-adversarial-network-p01] Given a training set, this technique learns to generate new data with the same statistics as the training set.
[src:image-super-resolution/generative-adversarial-network-p01] For example, a GAN trained on photographs can generate new photographs that look at least superficially authentic to human observers, having many realistic characteristics.
[src:image-super-resolution/generative-adversarial-network-p01] Though originally proposed as a form of generative model for unsupervised learning, GANs have also proved useful for semi-supervised learning, fully supervised learning, and reinforcement learning.
[src:image-super-resolution/generative-adversarial-network-p01] The core idea of a GAN is based on the "indirect" training through the discriminator, another neural network that can tell how "realistic" the input seems, which itself is also being updated dynamically.
[src:image-super-resolution/generative-adversarial-network-p01] This means that the generator is not trained to minimize the distance to a specific image, but rather to fool the discriminator.
[src:image-super-resolution/generative-adversarial-network-p01] This enables the model to learn in an unsupervised manner.
[src:image-super-resolution/generative-adversarial-network-p01] GANs are similar to mimicry in evolutionary biology, with an evolutionary arms race between both networks.
[src:image-super-resolution/generative-adversarial-network-p01] The generator's task is to approach $\mu _{G}\approx \mu _{\text{ref}}$ , that is, to match its own output distribution as closely as possible to the reference distribution.
[src:image-super-resolution/generative-adversarial-network-p01] The discriminator's task is to output a value close to 1 when the input appears to be from the reference distribution, and to output a value close to 0 when the input looks like it came from the generator distribution.
[src:image-super-resolution/generative-adversarial-network-p01] The *generative* network generates candidates while the *discriminative* network evaluates them.
[src:image-super-resolution/generative-adversarial-network-p01] This creates a contest based on data distributions, where the generator learns to map from a latent space to the true data distribution, aiming to produce candidates that the discriminator cannot distinguish from real data.
[src:image-super-resolution/generative-adversarial-network-p01] The discriminator's goal is to correctly identify these candidates, but as the generator improves, its task becomes more challenging, increasing the discriminator's error rate.
[src:image-super-resolution/generative-adversarial-network-p01] A known dataset serves as the initial training data for the discriminator.
[src:image-super-resolution/generative-adversarial-network-p01] Training involves presenting it with samples from the training dataset until it achieves acceptable accuracy.
[src:image-super-resolution/generative-adversarial-network-p01] The generator is trained based on whether it succeeds in fooling the discriminator.
[src:image-super-resolution/generative-adversarial-network-p01] Typically, the generator is seeded with randomized input that is sampled from a predefined latent space (e.g. a multivariate normal distribution).
[src:image-super-resolution/generative-adversarial-network-p01] Thereafter, candidates synthesized by the generator are evaluated by the discriminator.
[src:image-super-resolution/generative-adversarial-network-p01] Independent backpropagation procedures are applied to both networks so that the generator produces better samples, while the discriminator becomes more skilled at flagging synthetic samples.
[src:image-super-resolution/generative-adversarial-network-p01] When used for image generation, the generator is typically a deconvolutional neural network, and the discriminator is a convolutional neural network.
[src:image-super-resolution/generative-adversarial-network-p01] GANs are **implicit generative models**, which means that they do not explicitly model the likelihood function nor provide a means for finding the latent variable corresponding to a given sample, unlike alternatives such as flow-based generative model.
[src:image-super-resolution/generative-adversarial-network-p01] Compared to fully visible belief networks such as WaveNet and PixelRNN and autoregressive models in general, GANs can generate one complete sample in one pass, rather than multiple passes through the network.
[src:image-super-resolution/generative-adversarial-network-p01] Compared to Boltzmann machines and linear ICA, there is no restriction on the type of function used by the network.
[src:image-super-resolution/generative-adversarial-network-p01] Since neural networks are universal approximators, GANs are asymptotically consistent.
[src:image-super-resolution/generative-adversarial-network-p01] Variational autoencoders might be universal approximators, but it is not proven as of 2017.
[src:image-super-resolution/generative-adversarial-network-p01] This section provides some of the mathematical theory behind these methods.
[src:image-super-resolution/generative-adversarial-network-p01] In modern probability theory based on measure theory, a probability space also needs to be equipped with a σ-algebra.
[src:image-super-resolution/generative-adversarial-network-p01] Since issues of measurability never arise in practice, these will not concern us further.
[src:image-super-resolution/generative-adversarial-network-p01] In the most generic version of the GAN game described above, the strategy set for the discriminator contains all Markov kernels $\mu _{D}:\Omega \to {\mathcal {P}}[0,1]$ , and the strategy set for the generator contains arbitrary probability distributions $\mu _{G}$ on $\Omega$ .
[src:image-super-resolution/generative-adversarial-network-p01] However, as shown below, the optimal discriminator strategy against any $\mu _{G}$ is deterministic, so there is no loss of generality in restricting the discriminator's strategies to deterministic functions $D:\Omega \to [0,1]$ .
[src:image-super-resolution/generative-adversarial-network-p01] In most applications, D is a deep neural network function.
[src:image-super-resolution/generative-adversarial-network-p01] As for the generator, while $\mu _{G}$ could theoretically be any computable probability distribution, in practice, it is usually implemented as a pushforward: $\mu _{G}=\mu _{Z}\circ G^{-1}$ .
[src:image-super-resolution/generative-adversarial-network-p01] That is, start with a random variable $z\sim \mu _{Z}$ , where $\mu _{Z}$ is a probability distribution that is easy to compute (such as the uniform distribution, or the Gaussian distribution), then define a function $G:\Omega _{Z}\to \Omega$ .
[src:image-super-resolution/generative-adversarial-network-p01] Then the distribution $\mu _{G}$ is the distribution of $G(z)$ .
[src:image-super-resolution/generative-adversarial-network-p01] Consequently, the generator's strategy is usually defined as just G , leaving $z\sim \mu _{Z}$ implicit.
[src:image-super-resolution/generative-adversarial-network-p01] The GAN architecture has two main components.
[src:image-super-resolution/generative-adversarial-network-p01] One is casting optimization into a game, of form $\min _{G}\max _{D}L(G,D)$ , which is different from the usual kind of optimization, of form $\min _{\theta }L(\theta )$ .
[src:image-super-resolution/generative-adversarial-network-p01] The other is the decomposition of $\mu _{G}$ into $\mu _{Z}\circ G^{-1}$ , which can be understood as a reparametrization trick.
[src:image-super-resolution/generative-adversarial-network-p01] To see its significance, one must compare GAN with previous methods for learning generative models, which were plagued with "intractable probabilistic computations that arise in maximum likelihood estimation and related strategies".
[src:image-super-resolution/generative-adversarial-network-p01] At the same time, Kingma and Welling and Rezende et al. developed the same idea of reparametrization into a general stochastic backpropagation method.
[src:image-super-resolution/generative-adversarial-network-p01] Among its first applications was the variational autoencoder.
[src:image-super-resolution/generative-adversarial-network-p01] If both the generator's and the discriminator's strategy sets are spanned by a finite number of strategies, then by the minimax theorem, $\min _{\mu _{G}}\max _{\mu _{D}}L(\mu _{G},\mu _{D})=\max _{\mu _{D}}\min _{\mu _{G}}L(\mu _{G},\mu _{D})$ that is, the move order does not matter.
[src:image-super-resolution/generative-adversarial-network-p01] However, since the strategy sets are both not finitely spanned, the minimax theorem does not apply, and the idea of an "equilibrium" becomes delicate.
[src:image-super-resolution/generative-adversarial-network-p01] For general games, these equilibria do not have to agree, or even to exist.
[src:image-super-resolution/generative-adversarial-network-p01] For the original GAN game, these equilibria all exist, and are all equal.
[src:image-super-resolution/generative-adversarial-network-p01] However, for more general GAN games, these do not necessarily exist, or agree.
[src:image-super-resolution/generative-adversarial-network-p01] where the derivative is the Radon–Nikodym derivative, and $D_{JS}$ is the Jensen–Shannon divergence.
[src:image-super-resolution/generative-adversarial-network-p01] The integrand is just the negative cross-entropy between two Bernoulli random variables with parameters $\rho _{\text{ref}}(x)$ and $D(x)$ .
[src:image-super-resolution/generative-adversarial-network-p01] That is, the generator perfectly mimics the reference, and the discriminator outputs ${\frac {1}{2}}$ deterministically on all inputs.
[src:image-super-resolution/generative-adversarial-network-p01] By Jensen's inequality, the discriminator can only improve by adopting the deterministic strategy of always playing $D(x)=\operatorname {E} _{y\sim \mu _{D}(x)}[y]$ .
[src:image-super-resolution/generative-adversarial-network-p01] When $\forall x\in \Omega ,\mu _{D}(x)=\delta _{\frac {1}{2}}$ , any strategy is optimal for the generator.
[src:image-super-resolution/generative-adversarial-network-p01] While the GAN game has a unique global equilibrium point when both the generator and discriminator have access to their entire strategy sets, the equilibrium is no longer guaranteed when they have a restricted strategy set.
[src:image-super-resolution/generative-adversarial-network-p01] In practice, the generator has access only to measures of form $\mu _{Z}\circ G_{\theta }^{-1}$ , where $G_{\theta }$ is a function computed by a neural network with parameters $\theta$ , and $\mu _{Z}$ is an easily sampled distribution, such as the uniform or normal distribution.
[src:image-super-resolution/generative-adversarial-network-p01] Similarly, the discriminator has access only to functions of form $D_{\zeta }$ , a function computed by a neural network with parameters $\zeta$ .
[src:image-super-resolution/generative-adversarial-network-p01] These restricted strategy sets take up a *vanishingly small proportion* of their entire strategy sets.
[src:image-super-resolution/generative-adversarial-network-p01] Further, even if an equilibrium still exists, it can only be found by searching in the high-dimensional space of all possible neural network functions.
[src:image-super-resolution/generative-adversarial-network-p01] The standard strategy of using gradient descent to find the equilibrium often does not work for GAN, and often the game "collapses" into one of several failure modes.
[src:image-super-resolution/generative-adversarial-network-p01] To improve the convergence stability, some training strategies start with an easier task, such as generating low-resolution images or simple images (one object with uniform background), and gradually increase the difficulty of the task during training.
[src:image-super-resolution/generative-adversarial-network-p01] This essentially translates to applying a curriculum learning scheme.
[src:image-super-resolution/generative-adversarial-network-p01] GANs often suffer from **mode collapse** where they fail to generalize properly, missing entire modes from the input data.
[src:image-super-resolution/generative-adversarial-network-p01] For example, a GAN trained on the MNIST dataset containing many samples of each digit might only generate pictures of digit 0.
[src:image-super-resolution/generative-adversarial-network-p01] This was termed "the Helvetica scenario".
[src:image-super-resolution/generative-adversarial-network-p01] A typical mechanism for mode collapse is the generator only generating one or a few of the likely values, or a very incomplete picture of the target distribution.
[src:image-super-resolution/generative-adversarial-network-p01] As the discriminator is only trained to distinguish real from fake samples, it will correctly identify the generated samples as real, but no penalty is imposed on the GAN's ability to generate data that represents the full range of the target distribution.
[src:image-super-resolution/generative-adversarial-network-p01] Weak discriminators, for instance underparametrized ones, or ones trained too slow compared to the generator, may as well be unable to fully discriminate over the entire support of the distribution, and only become able to correctly discriminate a very incomplete part of the target distribution.
[src:image-super-resolution/generative-adversarial-network-p01] Some researchers perceive the root problem to be a weak discriminative network that fails to notice the pattern of omission, while others assign blame to a bad choice of objective function.
[src:image-super-resolution/generative-adversarial-network-p01] Many solutions have been proposed, but it is still an open problem.
[src:image-super-resolution/generative-adversarial-network-p01] Even the state-of-the-art architecture, BigGAN (2019), could not avoid mode collapse.
[src:image-super-resolution/generative-adversarial-network-p01] The authors resorted to "allowing collapse to occur at the later stages of training, by which time a model is sufficiently trained to achieve good results".
[src:image-super-resolution/generative-adversarial-network-p01] The **two time-scale update rule (TTUR)** is proposed to make GAN convergence more stable by making the learning rate of the generator lower than that of the discriminator.
[src:image-super-resolution/generative-adversarial-network-p01] They prove that when trained this way, GANs "converge, under mild assumptions to a stationary local Nash equilibrium".
[src:image-super-resolution/generative-adversarial-network-p01] They further show that this property extends to the use of the Adam optimizer, which is commonly used in stochastic gradient descent.
[src:image-super-resolution/generative-adversarial-network-p01] A local Nash equilibrium in no way signifies an absence of mode collapse - for instance, a GAN trained on MNIST collapsed to generating a single digit may satisfy the hypotheses of the paper, while still presenting mode collapse.
[src:image-super-resolution/generative-adversarial-network-p01] Conversely, if the discriminator learns too fast compared to the generator, then the discriminator could almost perfectly distinguish $\mu _{G_{\theta }},\mu _{\text{ref}}$ .
[src:image-super-resolution/generative-adversarial-network-p01] In such case, the generator $G_{\theta }$ could be stuck with a very high loss no matter which direction it changes its $\theta$ , meaning that the gradient $\nabla _{\theta }L(G_{\theta },D_{\zeta })$ would be close to zero.
[src:image-super-resolution/generative-adversarial-network-p01] In such case, the generator cannot learn, a case of the **vanishing gradient** problem.
[src:image-super-resolution/generative-adversarial-network-p01] Intuitively speaking, the discriminator is too good, and since the generator cannot take any small step (only small steps are considered in gradient descent) to improve its payoff, it does not even try.
[src:image-super-resolution/generative-adversarial-network-p01] One important method for solving this problem is the Wasserstein GAN.
[src:image-super-resolution/generative-adversarial-network-p01] Many papers that propose new GAN architectures for image generation report how their architectures break the state of the art on FID or IS.
[src:image-super-resolution/generative-adversarial-network-p01] The model is finetuned so that it can approximate $\|f_{\theta }(x)-f_{\theta }(x')\|\approx \operatorname {perceptual~difference} (x,x')$ .
[src:image-super-resolution/generative-adversarial-network-p01] This finetuned model is then used to define $\operatorname {LPIPS} (x,x'):=\|f_{\theta }(x)-f_{\theta }(x')\|$ .
[src:image-super-resolution/generative-adversarial-network-p01] Other evaluation methods are reviewed in.
[src:image-super-resolution/generative-adversarial-network-p01] There is a veritable zoo of GAN variants.
[src:image-super-resolution/generative-adversarial-network-p01] Conditional GANs are similar to standard GANs except they allow the model to conditionally generate samples based on additional information.
[src:image-super-resolution/generative-adversarial-network-p01] For example, if we want to generate a cat face given a dog picture, we could use a conditional GAN.
[src:image-super-resolution/generative-adversarial-network-p01] The generator in a GAN game generates $\mu _{G}$ , a probability distribution on the probability space $\Omega$ .
[src:image-super-resolution/generative-adversarial-network-p01] This leads to the idea of a conditional GAN, where instead of generating one probability distribution on $\Omega$ , the generator generates a different probability distribution $\mu _{G}(c)$ on $\Omega$ , for each given class label c .
[src:image-super-resolution/generative-adversarial-network-p01] For example, for generating images that look like ImageNet, the generator should be able to generate a picture of cat when given the class label "cat".
[src:image-super-resolution/generative-adversarial-network-p01] In the original paper, the authors noted that GAN can be trivially extended to conditional GAN by providing the labels to both the generator and the discriminator.
[src:image-super-resolution/generative-adversarial-network-p01] In 2017, a conditional GAN learned to generate 1000 image classes of ImageNet.
[src:image-super-resolution/generative-adversarial-network-p01] The GAN game is a general framework and can be run with any reasonable parametrization of the generator G and discriminator D .
[src:image-super-resolution/generative-adversarial-network-p01] In the original paper, the authors demonstrated it using multilayer perceptron networks and convolutional neural networks.
[src:image-super-resolution/generative-adversarial-network-p01] Many alternative architectures have been tried.
[src:image-super-resolution/generative-adversarial-network-p01] Many GAN variants are merely obtained by changing the loss functions for the generator and discriminator.
[src:image-super-resolution/generative-adversarial-network-p01] This objective for generator was recommended in the original paper for faster convergence. $L_{G}=\operatorname {E} _{x\sim \mu _{G}}[\ln D(x)]$ The effect of using this objective is analyzed in Section 2.2.2 of Arjovsky et al.
[src:image-super-resolution/generative-adversarial-network-p01] When the discriminator is optimal, the generator gradient is the same as in maximum likelihood estimation, even though GAN cannot perform maximum likelihood estimation *itself*.
[src:image-super-resolution/generative-adversarial-network-p01] One of its purposes is to solve the problem of mode collapse (see above).
[src:image-super-resolution/generative-adversarial-network-p01] The authors claim "In no experiment did we see evidence of mode collapse for the WGAN algorithm".
[src:image-super-resolution/generative-adversarial-network-p01] An adversarial autoencoder (AAE) is more autoencoder than GAN.
[src:image-super-resolution/generative-adversarial-network-p01] The idea is to start with a plain autoencoder, but train a discriminator to discriminate the latent vectors from a reference distribution (often the normal distribution).
[src:image-super-resolution/generative-adversarial-network-p01] In conditional GAN, the generator receives both a noise vector z and a label c , and produces an image $G(z,c)$ .
[src:image-super-resolution/generative-adversarial-network-p01] The discriminator receives image-label pairs $(x,c)$ , and computes $D(x,c)$ .
[src:image-super-resolution/generative-adversarial-network-p01] When the training dataset is unlabeled, conditional GAN does not work directly.
[src:image-super-resolution/generative-adversarial-network-p01] The standard GAN generator is a function of type $G:\Omega _{Z}\to \Omega _{X}$ , that is, it is a mapping from a latent space $\Omega _{Z}$ to the image space $\Omega _{X}$ .
[src:image-super-resolution/generative-adversarial-network-p01] This can be understood as a "decoding" process, whereby every latent vector $z\in \Omega _{Z}$ is a code for an image $x\in \Omega _{X}$ , and the generator performs the decoding.
[src:image-super-resolution/generative-adversarial-network-p01] This naturally leads to the idea of training another network that performs "encoding", creating an autoencoder out of the encoder-generator pair.
[src:image-super-resolution/generative-adversarial-network-p01] Already in the original paper, the authors noted that "Learned approximate inference can be performed by training an auxiliary network to predict z given x ".
[src:image-super-resolution/generative-adversarial-network-p01] The bidirectional GAN architecture performs exactly this.
[src:image-super-resolution/generative-adversarial-network-p01] Applications of bidirectional models include semi-supervised learning, interpretable machine learning, and neural machine translation.
[src:image-super-resolution/generative-adversarial-network-p01] CycleGAN is an architecture for performing translations between two domains, such as between photos of horses and photos of zebras, or photos of night cities and photos of day cities.
[src:image-super-resolution/generative-adversarial-network-p01] Unlike previous work like pix2pix, which requires paired training data, cycleGAN requires no paired data.
[src:image-super-resolution/generative-adversarial-network-p01] The BigGAN is essentially a self-attention GAN trained on a large scale (up to 80 million parameters) to generate large images of ImageNet (up to 512 x 512 resolution), with numerous engineering tricks to make it converge.
[src:image-super-resolution/generative-adversarial-network-p01] When there is insufficient training data, the reference distribution $\mu _{\text{ref}}$ cannot be well-approximated by the empirical distribution given by the training dataset.
[src:image-super-resolution/generative-adversarial-network-p01] In such cases, data augmentation can be applied, to allow training GAN on smaller datasets.
[src:image-super-resolution/generative-adversarial-network-p01] Naïve data augmentation, however, brings its problems.
[src:image-super-resolution/generative-adversarial-network-p01] The result of such training would be a generator that mimics $\mu _{\text{ref}}'$ .
[src:image-super-resolution/generative-adversarial-network-p01] For example, it would generate images that look like they are randomly cropped, if the data augmentation uses random cropping.
[src:image-super-resolution/generative-adversarial-network-p01] The StyleGAN-2-ADA paper points out a further point on data augmentation: it must be *invertible*.
[src:image-super-resolution/generative-adversarial-network-p01] Continue with the example of generating ImageNet pictures.
[src:image-super-resolution/generative-adversarial-network-p01] They would have exactly the same expected loss, and so neither is preferred over the other.
[src:image-super-resolution/generative-adversarial-network-p01] The solution is to only use invertible data augmentation: instead of "randomly rotate the picture by 0, 90, 180, 270 degrees with *equal* probability", use "randomly rotate the picture by 90, 180, 270 degrees with 0.1 probability, and keep the picture as it is with 0.7 probability".
[src:image-super-resolution/generative-adversarial-network-p01] This way, the generator is still rewarded to keep images oriented the same way as un-augmented ImageNet pictures.
[src:image-super-resolution/generative-adversarial-network-p01] Abstractly, the effect of randomly sampling transformations $T:\Omega \to \Omega$ from the distribution $\mu _{\text{trans}}$ is to define a Markov kernel $K_{\text{trans}}:\Omega \to {\mathcal {P}}(\Omega )$ .
[src:image-super-resolution/generative-adversarial-network-p01] Then, the data-augmented GAN game pushes the generator to find some ${\hat {\mu }}_{G}\in {\mathcal {P}}(\Omega )$ , such that $K_{\text{trans}}*\mu _{\text{ref}}=K_{\text{trans}}*{\hat {\mu }}_{G}$ where * is the Markov kernel convolution.
[src:image-super-resolution/generative-adversarial-network-p01] Also by definition, if the data-augmentation method is invertible, then using it in a GAN game does not change the optimal strategy ${\hat {\mu }}_{G}$ for the generator, which is still $\mu _{\text{ref}}$ .
[src:image-super-resolution/generative-adversarial-network-p01] With that, we can recover $\mu$ by running the heat equation *backwards in time* for $\epsilon ^{2}/4$ .
[src:image-super-resolution/generative-adversarial-network-p01] More examples of invertible data augmentations are found in the paper.
[src:image-super-resolution/generative-adversarial-network-p01] SinGAN pushes data augmentation to the limit, by using only a single image as training data and performing data augmentation on it.
[src:image-super-resolution/generative-adversarial-network-p01] The GAN architecture is adapted to this training method by using a multi-scale pipeline.
[src:image-super-resolution/generative-adversarial-network-p01] The discriminator is decomposed into a pyramid as well.
[src:image-super-resolution/generative-adversarial-network-p01] The StyleGAN family is a series of architectures published by Nvidia's research division.
[src:image-super-resolution/generative-adversarial-network-p01] Progressive GAN is a method for training GAN for large-scale image generation stably, by growing a GAN generator from small to large scale in a pyramidal fashion.
[src:image-super-resolution/generative-adversarial-network-p01] Like SinGAN, it decomposes the generator as $G=G_{1}\circ G_{2}\circ \cdots \circ G_{N}$ , and the discriminator as $D=D_{1}\circ D_{2}\circ \cdots \circ D_{N}$ .
[src:image-super-resolution/generative-adversarial-network-p01] During training, at first only $G_{N},D_{N}$ are used in a GAN game to generate 4x4 images.
[src:image-super-resolution/generative-adversarial-network-p01] Then $G_{N-1},D_{N-1}$ are added to reach the second stage of GAN game, to generate 8x8 images, and so on, until we reach a GAN game to generate 1024x1024 images.
[src:image-super-resolution/generative-adversarial-network-p01] To avoid shock between stages of the GAN game, each new layer is "blended in" (Figure 2 of the paper).
[src:image-super-resolution/generative-adversarial-network-p01] StyleGAN-1 is designed as a combination of Progressive GAN with neural style transfer.
[src:image-super-resolution/generative-adversarial-network-p01] The key architectural choice of StyleGAN-1 is a progressive growth mechanism, similar to Progressive GAN.
[src:image-super-resolution/generative-adversarial-network-p01] Each generated image starts as a constant $4\times 4\times 512$ array, and repeatedly passed through style blocks.
[src:image-super-resolution/generative-adversarial-network-p01] Each style block applies a "style latent vector" via affine transform ("adaptive instance normalization"), similar to how neural style transfer uses Gramian matrix.
[src:image-super-resolution/generative-adversarial-network-p01] It then adds noise, and normalize (subtract the mean, then divide by the variance).
[src:image-super-resolution/generative-adversarial-network-p01] After training, multiple style latent vectors can be fed into each style block.
[src:image-super-resolution/generative-adversarial-network-p01] Those fed to the lower layers control the large-scale styles, and those fed to the higher layers control the fine-detail styles.
[src:image-super-resolution/generative-adversarial-network-p01] Style-mixing between two images $x,x'$ can be performed as well.
[src:image-super-resolution/generative-adversarial-network-p01] First, run a gradient descent to find $z,z'$ such that $G(z)\approx x,G(z')\approx x'$ .
[src:image-super-resolution/generative-adversarial-network-p01] This is called "projecting an image back to style latent space".
[src:image-super-resolution/generative-adversarial-network-p01] Then, z can be fed to the lower style blocks, and $z'$ to the higher style blocks, to generate a composite image that has the large-scale style of x , and the fine-detail style of $x'$ .
[src:image-super-resolution/generative-adversarial-network-p01] Multiple images can also be composed this way.
[src:image-super-resolution/generative-adversarial-network-p01] StyleGAN-2 improves upon StyleGAN-1, by using the style latent vector to transform the convolution layer's weights instead, thus solving the "blob" problem.
[src:image-super-resolution/generative-adversarial-network-p01] This was updated by the StyleGAN-2-ADA ("ADA" stands for "adaptive"), which uses invertible data augmentation as described above.
[src:image-super-resolution/generative-adversarial-network-p01] It also tunes the amount of data augmentation applied by starting at zero, and gradually increasing it until an "overfitting heuristic" reaches a target level, thus the name "adaptive".
[src:image-super-resolution/generative-adversarial-network-p01] StyleGAN-3 improves upon StyleGAN-2 by solving the "texture sticking" problem, which can be seen in the official videos.
[src:image-super-resolution/generative-adversarial-network-p01] They analyzed the problem by the Nyquist–Shannon sampling theorem, and argued that the layers in the generator learned to exploit the high-frequency signal in the pixels they operate upon.
[src:image-super-resolution/generative-adversarial-network-p01] To solve this, they proposed imposing strict lowpass filters between each generator's layers, so that the generator is forced to operate on the pixels in a way faithful to the continuous signals they represent, rather than operate on them as merely discrete signals.
[src:image-super-resolution/generative-adversarial-network-p01] They further imposed rotational and translational invariance by using more signal filters.
[src:image-super-resolution/generative-adversarial-network-p01] The resulting StyleGAN-3 is able to solve the texture sticking problem, as well as generating images that rotate and translate smoothly.
[src:image-super-resolution/generative-adversarial-network-p01] Other than for generative and discriminative modelling of data, GANs have been used for other things.
[src:image-super-resolution/generative-adversarial-network-p01] GANs have been used for transfer learning to enforce the alignment of the latent feature space, such as in deep reinforcement learning.
[src:image-super-resolution/generative-adversarial-network-p01] This works by feeding the embeddings of the source and target task to the discriminator which tries to guess the context.
[src:image-super-resolution/generative-adversarial-network-p01] The resulting loss is then (inversely) backpropagated through the encoder.
[src:image-super-resolution/generative-adversarial-network-p02] GAN-generated molecules were validated experimentally in mice.
[src:image-super-resolution/generative-adversarial-network-p02] One of the major concerns in medical imaging is preserving patient privacy.
[src:image-super-resolution/generative-adversarial-network-p02] Due to these reasons, researchers often face difficulties in obtaining medical images for their research purposes.
[src:image-super-resolution/generative-adversarial-network-p02] GAN has been used for generating synthetic medical images, such as MRI and PET images to address this challenge.
[src:image-super-resolution/generative-adversarial-network-p02] GAN can be used to detect glaucomatous images helping the early diagnosis which is essential to avoid partial or total loss of vision.
[src:image-super-resolution/generative-adversarial-network-p02] GANs have been used to create forensic facial reconstructions of deceased historical figures.
[src:image-super-resolution/generative-adversarial-network-p02] Concerns have been raised about the potential use of GAN-based human image synthesis for sinister purposes, e.g., to produce fake, possibly incriminating, photographs and videos.
[src:image-super-resolution/generative-adversarial-network-p02] GANs can be used to generate unique, realistic profile photos of people who do not exist, in order to automate creation of fake social media profiles.
[src:image-super-resolution/generative-adversarial-network-p02] Both bills were authored by Assembly member Marc Berman and signed by Governor Gavin Newsom.
[src:image-super-resolution/generative-adversarial-network-p02] DARPA's Media Forensics program studies ways to counteract fake media, including fake media produced using GANs.
[src:image-super-resolution/generative-adversarial-network-p02] Some have worked with using GAN for artistic creativity, as "creative adversarial network".
[src:image-super-resolution/generative-adversarial-network-p02] A GAN, trained on a set of 15,000 portraits from WikiArt from the 14th to the 19th century, created the 2018 painting *Edmond de Belamy,* which sold for US$432,500.
[src:image-super-resolution/generative-adversarial-network-p02] GANs were used by the video game modding community to up-scale low-resolution 2D textures in old video games by recreating them in 4k or higher resolutions via image training, and then down-sampling them to fit the game's native resolution (resembling supersampling anti-aliasing).
[src:image-super-resolution/generative-adversarial-network-p02] In 2020, Artbreeder was used to create the main antagonist in the sequel to the psychological web horror series *Ben Drowned*.
[src:image-super-resolution/generative-adversarial-network-p02] The author would later go on to praise GAN applications for their ability to help generate assets for independent artists who are short on budget and manpower.
[src:image-super-resolution/generative-adversarial-network-p02] In May 2020, Nvidia researchers taught an AI system (termed "GameGAN") to recreate the game of *Pac-Man* simply by watching it being played.
[src:image-super-resolution/generative-adversarial-network-p02] In August 2019, a large dataset consisting of 12,197 MIDI songs each with paired lyrics and melody alignment was created for neural melody generation from lyrics using conditional GAN-LSTM (refer to sources at GitHub AI Melody Generation from Lyrics).
[src:image-super-resolution/generative-adversarial-network-p02] In 1991, Juergen Schmidhuber published "artificial curiosity", neural networks in a zero-sum game.
[src:image-super-resolution/generative-adversarial-network-p02] The first network is a generative model that models a probability distribution over output patterns.
[src:image-super-resolution/generative-adversarial-network-p02] The second network learns by gradient descent to predict the reactions of the environment to these patterns.
[src:image-super-resolution/generative-adversarial-network-p02] GANs can be regarded as a case where the environmental reaction is 1 or 0 depending on whether the first network's output is in a given set.
[src:image-super-resolution/generative-adversarial-network-p02] Other people had similar ideas but did not develop them similarly.
[src:image-super-resolution/generative-adversarial-network-p02] An idea involving adversarial networks was published in a 2010 blog post by Olli Niemitalo.
[src:image-super-resolution/generative-adversarial-network-p02] This idea was never implemented and did not involve stochasticity in the generator and thus was not a generative model.
[src:image-super-resolution/generative-adversarial-network-p02] An idea similar to GANs was used to model animal behavior by Wei Li, Melvin Gauci and Roderich Gross in 2013.
[src:image-super-resolution/generative-adversarial-network-p02] Another inspiration for GANs was noise-contrastive estimation, which uses the same loss function as GANs and which Goodfellow studied during his PhD in 2010–2014.
[src:image-super-resolution/generative-adversarial-network-p02] Adversarial machine learning has other uses besides generative modeling and can be applied to models other than neural networks.
[src:image-super-resolution/generative-adversarial-network-p02] In control theory, adversarial learning based on neural networks was used in 2006 to train robust controllers in a game theoretic sense, by alternating the iterations between a minimizer policy, the controller, and a maximizer policy, the disturbance.
[src:image-super-resolution/generative-adversarial-network-p02] In 2017, a GAN was used for image enhancement focusing on realistic textures rather than pixel-accuracy, producing a higher image quality at high magnification.
[src:image-super-resolution/generative-adversarial-network-p02] In 2017, the first faces were generated.
[src:image-super-resolution/generative-adversarial-network-p02] These were exhibited in February 2018 at the Grand Palais.
[src:image-super-resolution/generative-adversarial-network-p02] Faces generated by StyleGAN in 2019 drew comparisons with Deepfakes.
[src:image-super-resolution/image-scaling] In computer graphics and digital imaging, **image scaling** is the resizing of a digital image.
[src:image-super-resolution/image-scaling] In video technology, the magnification of digital material is known as upscaling or resolution enhancement.
[src:image-super-resolution/image-scaling] When scaling a vector graphic image, the graphic primitives that make up the image can be rendered using geometric transformations at any resolution with no loss of image quality.
[src:image-super-resolution/image-scaling] When scaling a raster graphics image, a new image with a higher or lower number of pixels must be generated.
[src:image-super-resolution/image-scaling] In the case of decreasing the pixel number (scaling down), this usually results in a visible quality loss.
[src:image-super-resolution/image-scaling] From the standpoint of digital signal processing, the scaling of raster graphics is a two-dimensional example of sample-rate conversion, the conversion of a discrete signal from a sampling rate (in this case, the local sampling rate) to another.
[src:image-super-resolution/image-scaling] Image scaling can be interpreted as a form of image resampling or image reconstruction from the view of the Nyquist sampling theorem.
[src:image-super-resolution/image-scaling] According to the theorem, downsampling to a smaller image from a higher-resolution original can only be carried out after applying a suitable 2D anti-aliasing filter to prevent aliasing artifacts.
[src:image-super-resolution/image-scaling] The image is reduced to the information that can be carried by the smaller image.
[src:image-super-resolution/image-scaling] In the case of up sampling, a reconstruction filter takes the place of the anti-aliasing filter.
[src:image-super-resolution/image-scaling] A more sophisticated approach to upscaling treats the problem as an inverse problem, solving the question of generating a plausible image that, when scaled down, would look like the input image.
[src:image-super-resolution/image-scaling] A variety of techniques have been applied for this, including optimization techniques with regularization terms and the use of machine learning from examples.
[src:image-super-resolution/image-scaling] An image size can be changed in several ways.
[src:image-super-resolution/image-scaling] One of the simpler ways of increasing image size is nearest-neighbor interpolation, replacing every pixel with the nearest pixel in the output; for upscaling, this means multiple pixels of the same color will be present.
[src:image-super-resolution/image-scaling] This can preserve sharp details but also introduce jaggedness in previously smooth images.
[src:image-super-resolution/image-scaling] 'Nearest' in nearest-neighbor does not have to be the mathematical nearest.
[src:image-super-resolution/image-scaling] One common implementation is to always round toward zero.
[src:image-super-resolution/image-scaling] Rounding this way produces fewer artifacts and is faster to calculate.
[src:image-super-resolution/image-scaling] This algorithm is often preferred for images which have little to no smooth edges.
[src:image-super-resolution/image-scaling] A common application of this can be found in pixel art.
[src:image-super-resolution/image-scaling] Bilinear interpolation works by interpolating pixel color values, introducing a continuous transition into the output even where the original material has discrete transitions.
[src:image-super-resolution/image-scaling] Although this is desirable for continuous-tone images, this algorithm reduces contrast (sharp edges) in a way that may be undesirable for line art.
[src:image-super-resolution/image-scaling] Bicubic interpolation yields substantially better results, with an increase in computational cost.
[src:image-super-resolution/image-scaling] Sinc resampling, in theory, provides the best possible reconstruction for a perfectly bandlimited signal.
[src:image-super-resolution/image-scaling] In practice, the assumptions behind sinc resampling are not completely met by real-world digital images.
[src:image-super-resolution/image-scaling] Lanczos resampling, an approximation to the sinc method, yields better results.
[src:image-super-resolution/image-scaling] Bicubic interpolation can be regarded as a computationally efficient approximation to Lanczos resampling.
[src:image-super-resolution/image-scaling] One weakness of bilinear, bicubic, and related algorithms is that they sample a specific number of pixels.
[src:image-super-resolution/image-scaling] When downscaling below a certain threshold, such as more than twice for all bi-sampling algorithms, the algorithms will sample non-adjacent pixels, which results in both losing data and rough results.
[src:image-super-resolution/image-scaling] The trivial solution to this issue is box sampling, which is to consider the target pixel a box on the original image and sample all pixels inside the box.
[src:image-super-resolution/image-scaling] This ensures that all input pixels contribute to the output.
[src:image-super-resolution/image-scaling] The major weakness of this algorithm is that it is hard to optimize.
[src:image-super-resolution/image-scaling] Another solution to the downscale problem of bi-sampling scaling is mipmaps.
[src:image-super-resolution/image-scaling] A mipmap is a prescaled set of downscaled copies.
[src:image-super-resolution/image-scaling] When downscaling, the nearest larger mipmap is used as the origin to ensure no scaling below the useful threshold of bilinear scaling.
[src:image-super-resolution/image-scaling] This algorithm is fast and easy to optimize.
[src:image-super-resolution/image-scaling] It is standard in many frameworks, such as OpenGL.
[src:image-super-resolution/image-scaling] The cost is using more image memory, exactly one-third more in the standard implementation.
[src:image-super-resolution/image-scaling] Simple interpolation based on the Fourier transform pads the frequency domain with zero components (a smooth window-based approach would reduce the ringing).
[src:image-super-resolution/image-scaling] Besides the good conservation (or recovery) of details, notable are the ringing and the circular bleeding of content from the left border to the right border (and the other way around).
[src:image-super-resolution/image-scaling] Edge-directed interpolation algorithms aim to preserve edges in the image after scaling, unlike other algorithms, which can introduce staircase artifacts.
[src:image-super-resolution/image-scaling] Examples of algorithms for this task include New Edge-Directed Interpolation (NEDI), Edge-Guided Image Interpolation (EGGI), Iterative Curvature-Based Interpolation (ICBI), and Directional Cubic Convolution Interpolation (DCCI).
[src:image-super-resolution/image-scaling] A 2013 analysis found that DCCI had the best scores in peak signal-to-noise ratio and structural similarity on a series of test images.
[src:image-super-resolution/image-scaling] For magnifying computer graphics with low resolution and/or few colors (usually from 2 to 256 colors), better results can be achieved by hqx or other pixel-art scaling algorithms.
[src:image-super-resolution/image-scaling] These produce sharp edges and maintain a high level of detail.
[src:image-super-resolution/image-scaling] Vector extraction, or vectorization, offers another approach.
[src:image-super-resolution/image-scaling] Vectorization first creates a resolution-independent vector representation of the graphic to be scaled.
[src:image-super-resolution/image-scaling] The resulting SVG vector file can then be exported and rendered at any required resolution without quality loss, serving directly as production-ready artwork for scalable display & printing.
[src:image-super-resolution/image-scaling] This technique is used by Adobe Illustrator, Live Trace, and Inkscape.
[src:image-super-resolution/image-scaling] Scalable Vector Graphics are well suited to simple geometric images, while photographs do not fare well with vectorization due to their complexity.
[src:image-super-resolution/image-scaling] This method uses machine learning for more detailed images, such as photographs and complex artwork.
[src:image-super-resolution/image-scaling] Programs that use this method include waifu2x, Imglarger and Neural Enhance.
[src:image-super-resolution/image-scaling] AI-driven upscaling software allows detail and sharpness to be added to historical photographs, where it is not present in the original.
[src:image-super-resolution/image-scaling] The availability of AI upscaling tools has led to confusion where a person believes that the upscaled version of a blurry image is genuinely showing them the subject of the original photograph.
[src:image-super-resolution/image-scaling] In 2025 a user of the social media site X posted an AI-upscaled version of a low resolution photo of Donald Trump that they had zoomed in on, and asked if anyone could "explain what the hell is happening to his forehead".
[src:image-super-resolution/image-scaling] Experts noted that the image had been distorted by the upscaling process, and that such tools "inevitably have to invent, or at least recreate, details that were or were not there".
[src:image-super-resolution/image-scaling] Image scaling is used in, among other applications, web browsers, image editors, image and file viewers, software magnifiers, digital zoom, the process of generating thumbnail images, and when outputting images through screens or printers.
[src:image-super-resolution/image-scaling] This application is the magnification of images for home theaters for HDTV-ready output devices from PAL-Resolution content, for example, from a DVD player.
[src:image-super-resolution/image-scaling] Upscaling is performed in real time, and the output signal is not saved.
[src:image-super-resolution/image-scaling] As pixel-art graphics are usually low-resolution, they rely on careful placement of individual pixels, often with a limited palette of colors.
[src:image-super-resolution/image-scaling] This results in graphics that rely on stylized visual cues to define complex shapes with little resolution, down to individual pixels.
[src:image-super-resolution/image-scaling] This makes scaling pixel art a particularly difficult problem.
[src:image-super-resolution/image-scaling] Specialized algorithms were developed to handle pixel-art graphics, as the traditional scaling algorithms do not take perceptual cues into account.
[src:image-super-resolution/image-scaling] Since a typical application is to improve the appearance of fourth-generation and earlier video games on arcade and console emulators, many are designed to run in real time for small input images at 60 frames per second.
[src:image-super-resolution/image-scaling] On fast hardware, these algorithms are suitable for gaming and other real-time image processing.
[src:image-super-resolution/image-scaling] These algorithms provide sharp, crisp graphics, while minimizing blur.
[src:image-super-resolution/image-scaling] Scaling art algorithms have been implemented in a wide range of emulators such as HqMAME and DOSBox, as well as 2D game engines and game engine recreations such as ScummVM.
[src:image-super-resolution/image-scaling] They gained recognition with gamers, for whom these technologies encouraged a revival of 1980s and 1990s gaming experiences.
[src:image-super-resolution/image-scaling] Such filters are currently used in commercial emulators on Xbox Live, Virtual Console, and PSN to allow classic low-resolution games to be more visually appealing on modern HD displays.
[src:image-super-resolution/image-scaling] Recently released games that incorporate these filters include *Sonic's Ultimate Genesis Collection*, *Castlevania: The Dracula X Chronicles*, *Castlevania: Symphony of the Night*, and *Akumajō Dracula X Chi no Rondo*.
[src:image-super-resolution/image-scaling] A number of companies have developed techniques to upscale video frames in real-time, such as when they are drawn on screen in a video game.
[src:image-super-resolution/image-scaling] Nvidia's deep learning super sampling (DLSS) uses deep learning to upsample lower-resolution images to a higher resolution for display on higher-resolution computer monitors.
[src:image-super-resolution/image-scaling] AMD's FidelityFX Super Resolution 1.0 (FSR) does not employ machine learning, instead using traditional hand-written algorithms to achieve spatial upscaling on traditional shading units.
[src:image-super-resolution/image-scaling] FSR 2.0 utilises temporal upscaling, again with a hand-tuned algorithm.
[src:image-super-resolution/image-scaling] FSR standardized presets are not enforced, and some titles such as *Dota 2* offer resolution sliders.
[src:image-super-resolution/image-scaling] Other technologies include Intel XeSS and Nvidia Image Scaler (NIS).
[src:image-super-resolution/super-resolution-imaging] In some radar and sonar imaging applications (e.g. magnetic resonance imaging (MRI), high-resolution computed tomography), subspace decomposition-based methods (e.g.
[src:image-super-resolution/super-resolution-imaging] MUSIC) and compressed sensing-based algorithms (e.g., SAMV) are employed to achieve SR over standard periodogram algorithm.
[src:image-super-resolution/super-resolution-imaging] Super-resolution imaging techniques are used in general image processing and in super-resolution microscopy.
[src:image-super-resolution/super-resolution-imaging] Substituting spatial-frequency bands: Though the bandwidth allowable by diffraction is fixed, it can be positioned anywhere in the spatial-frequency spectrum.
[src:image-super-resolution/super-resolution-imaging] Dark-field illumination in microscopy is an example.
[src:image-super-resolution/super-resolution-imaging] An image is formed using the normal passband of the optical device.
[src:image-super-resolution/super-resolution-imaging] Then, some known light structure (for example, a set of light fringes) is superimposed on the target.
[src:image-super-resolution/super-resolution-imaging] The image now contains components resulting from the combination of the target and the superimposed light structure, e.g. moiré fringes, and carries information about target detail which simple unstructured illumination does not.
[src:image-super-resolution/super-resolution-imaging] The “superresolved” components, however, need disentangling to be revealed.
[src:image-super-resolution/super-resolution-imaging] For an example, see structured illumination (figure to left).
[src:image-super-resolution/super-resolution-imaging] If a target has no special polarization or wavelength properties, two polarization states or non-overlapping wavelength regions can be used to encode target details, one in a spatial-frequency band inside the cut-off limit the other beyond it.
[src:image-super-resolution/super-resolution-imaging] Both would use normal passband transmission but are then separately decoded to reconstitute target structure with extended resolution.
[src:image-super-resolution/super-resolution-imaging] Super-resolution microscopy is generally discussed within the realm of conventional optical imagery.
[src:image-super-resolution/super-resolution-imaging] However, modern technology allows the probing of electromagnetic disturbance within molecular distances of the source, which has superior resolution properties.
[src:image-super-resolution/super-resolution-imaging] See also evanescent waves and the development of the new super lens.
[src:image-super-resolution/super-resolution-imaging] When an image is degraded by noise, the resolution may be improved by averaging multiple exposures.
[src:image-super-resolution/super-resolution-imaging] Known defects in a given imaging situation, such as defocus or aberrations, can sometimes be mitigated in whole or in part by suitable spatial-frequency filtering of even a single image.
[src:image-super-resolution/super-resolution-imaging] Such procedures all stay within the diffraction-mandated passband, and do not extend it.
[src:image-super-resolution/super-resolution-imaging] The location of a single source can be determined by computing the "center of gravity" (centroid) of the light distribution extending over several adjacent pixels (see figure on the left).
[src:image-super-resolution/super-resolution-imaging] Provided that there is enough light, this can be achieved with arbitrary precision, very much better than pixel width of the detecting apparatus and the resolution limit for the decision of whether the source is single or double.
[src:image-super-resolution/super-resolution-imaging] It is also the mechanism underlying visual hyperacuity.
[src:image-super-resolution/super-resolution-imaging] Some object features, though beyond the diffraction limit, may be known to be associated with other object features that are within the limits and hence contained in the image.
[src:image-super-resolution/super-resolution-imaging] Then conclusions can be drawn, using statistical methods, from the available image data about the presence of the full object.
[src:image-super-resolution/super-resolution-imaging] The classical example is Toraldo di Francia's proposition of judging whether an image is that of a single or double star by determining whether its width exceeds the spread from a single star.
[src:image-super-resolution/super-resolution-imaging] The approach can take the form of extrapolating the image in the frequency domain, by assuming that the object is an analytic function, and that we can exactly know the function values in some interval.
[src:image-super-resolution/super-resolution-imaging] This method is severely limited by the ever-present noise in digital imaging systems, but it can work for radar, astronomy, microscopy or magnetic resonance imaging.
[src:image-super-resolution/super-resolution-imaging] More recently, a fast single image super-resolution algorithm based on a closed-form solution to *$\ell _{2}-\ell _{2}$* problems has been proposed and demonstrated to accelerate most of the existing Bayesian super-resolution methods significantly.
[src:image-super-resolution/super-resolution-imaging] Geometrical SR reconstruction algorithms are possible if and only if the input low resolution images have been under-sampled and therefore contain aliasing.
[src:image-super-resolution/super-resolution-imaging] Because of this aliasing, the high-frequency content of the desired reconstruction image is embedded in the low-frequency content of each of the observed images.
[src:image-super-resolution/super-resolution-imaging] In practice, this frequency-based approach is not used for reconstruction, but even in the case of spatial approaches (e.g. shift-add fusion), the presence of aliasing is still a necessary condition for SR reconstruction.
[src:image-super-resolution/super-resolution-imaging] There are many both single-frame and multiple-frame variants of SR.
[src:image-super-resolution/super-resolution-imaging] Multiple-frame SR uses the sub-pixel shifts between multiple low resolution images of the same scene.
[src:image-super-resolution/super-resolution-imaging] It creates an improved resolution image fusing information from all low resolution images, and the created higher resolution images are better descriptions of the scene.
[src:image-super-resolution/super-resolution-imaging] Single-frame SR methods attempt to magnify the image without producing blur.
[src:image-super-resolution/super-resolution-imaging] These methods use other parts of the low resolution images, or other unrelated images, to guess what the high-resolution image should look like.
[src:image-super-resolution/super-resolution-imaging] Algorithms can also be divided by their domain: frequency or space domain.
[src:image-super-resolution/super-resolution-imaging] Originally, super-resolution methods worked well only on grayscale images, but researchers have found methods to adapt them to color camera images.
[src:image-super-resolution/super-resolution-imaging] Recently, the use of super-resolution for 3D data has also been shown.
[src:image-super-resolution/super-resolution-imaging] Research into using neural network computing to perform super-resolution image construction.
[src:image-super-resolution/super-resolution-imaging] For example, deep convolutional networks were used to generate a 1500x scanning electron microscope image from a 20x microscopic image of pollen grains.
[src:image-super-resolution/super-resolution-imaging] However, while this technique can increase the information content of an image, there is no guarantee that the upscaled features actually exist in the original image.
[src:image-super-resolution/super-resolution-imaging] For this reason deep convolutional upscalers are not appropriate for applications involving ambiguous inputs where the presence or absence of a single feature is critical.
[src:image-super-resolution/super-resolution-imaging] Hallucinated details in images taken for medical diagnosis, as an example, could be problematic.
[src:image-super-resolution/upsampling] In digital signal processing, **upsampling**, **expansion**, and **interpolation** are terms associated with the process of resampling in a multi-rate digital signal processing system.
[src:image-super-resolution/upsampling] *Upsampling* can be synonymous with *expansion*, or it can describe an entire process of *expansion* and filtering (*interpolation*).
[src:image-super-resolution/upsampling] When upsampling is performed on a sequence of samples of a *signal* or other continuous function, it produces an approximation of the sequence that would have been obtained by sampling the signal at a higher rate (or density, as in the case of a photograph).
[src:image-super-resolution/upsampling] For example, if compact disc audio at 44,100 samples/second is upsampled by a factor of 5/4, the resulting sample-rate is 55,125.
[src:image-super-resolution/upsampling] Interpolation**:** Smooth out the discontinuities using a lowpass filter, which replaces the zeros.
[src:image-super-resolution/upsampling] In this application, the filter is called an **interpolation filter**, and its design is discussed below.
[src:image-super-resolution/upsampling] When the interpolation filter is an FIR type, its efficiency can be improved, because the zeros contribute nothing to its dot product calculations.
[src:image-super-resolution/upsampling] It is an easy matter to omit them from both the data stream and the calculations.
[src:image-super-resolution/upsampling] where the h sequence is the impulse response of the interpolation filter, and K is the largest value of k for which $h[j+kL]$ is non-zero.
[src:image-super-resolution/upsampling] In the case $L=2,$ function h can be designed as a half-band filter, where almost half of the coefficients are zero and need not be included in the dot products.
[src:image-super-resolution/upsampling] Impulse response coefficients taken at intervals of L form a subsequence, and there are L such subsequences (called **phases**) multiplexed together.
[src:image-super-resolution/upsampling] Each of L phases of the impulse response is filtering the same sequential values of the x data stream and producing one of L sequential output values.
[src:image-super-resolution/upsampling] In some multi-processor architectures, these dot products are performed simultaneously, in which case it is called a **polyphase** filter.
[src:image-super-resolution/upsampling] For completeness, we now mention that a possible, but unlikely, implementation of each phase is to replace the coefficients of the other phases with zeros in a copy of the h array, and process the $x_{L}[n]$ sequence at L times faster than the original input rate.
[src:image-super-resolution/upsampling] The desired y sequence is the sum of the phases, where $L-1$ terms of the each sum are identically zero.
[src:image-super-resolution/upsampling] Computing $L-1$ zeros between the useful outputs of a phase and adding them to a sum is effectively decimation.
[src:image-super-resolution/upsampling] It's the same result as not computing them at all.
[src:image-super-resolution/upsampling] That equivalence is known as the *second Noble identity*.
[src:image-super-resolution/upsampling] It is sometimes used in derivations of the polyphase method.
